// ── 365 scriptures by month/day ───────────────────────────────────────────────
// Themes: Jan=New Beginnings, Feb=Identity, Mar=Renewal, Apr=Hope,
//         May=Strength, Jun=Endurance, Jul=Freedom, Aug=Body as Temple,
//         Sep=Discipline, Oct=Gratitude, Nov=Rest, Dec=Light & Reflection

const BY_MONTH = {
  1: [
    { v:"This means that anyone who belongs to Christ has become a new person. The old life is gone; a new life has begun!", r:"2 Corinthians 5:17", d:"The moment you gave your life to Christ, something ended and something entirely new began. Not improved, not patched up, not a better version of who you were before — new. God does not renovate people — he resurrects them. Whatever you have been carrying from your past, whatever identity was handed to you by your failures or your wounds or the people who defined you before you knew who you really were, it does not have to follow you anymore — you are not who you were — you belong to Christ now and that changes everything." },
    { v:"For I am about to do something new. See, I have already begun! Do you not see it?", r:"Isaiah 43:19", d:"God is not waiting for your life to settle down before he starts moving. He is already at work in the middle of the uncertainty, the transition, the season that has not made sense yet. He says see it, as if the evidence is already there if you are willing to look. The new thing is not coming eventually — it has already begun — your job is not to manufacture the breakthrough. Your job is to stay open to what God is already doing right in front of you." },
    { v:"The faithful love of the Lord never ends! His mercies never cease. Great is his faithfulness; his mercies begin afresh each morning.", r:"Lamentations 3:22–23", d:"Jeremiah wrote this from the ruins of Jerusalem. The city had been destroyed, the temple burned, the people dragged into exile. He was not writing from a comfortable season or a moment of clarity — he was sitting in ash. And from that place he chose to hold onto one thing: God's mercies are new every single morning. Not because the circumstances improved overnight but because God's character does not change with the situation. Whatever you are waking up to today, his mercy is already there waiting for you." },
    { v:"For I know the plans I have for you, says the Lord. They are plans for good and not for disaster, to give you a future and a hope.", r:"Jeremiah 29:11", d:"God spoke this promise to people who were in the middle of seventy years of captivity — not at the end — not after they got out — in the middle of it. The plans he has for you are not canceled by your hard season. They are not on hold while you get through this. He is working them out right now in ways you cannot see yet. You do not have to understand the process to trust the one who is running it — his plans are good. They hold even when your circumstances do not feel like it." },
    { v:"I focus on this one thing: forgetting the past and looking forward to what lies ahead.", r:"Philippians 3:13", d:"Paul had every reason to be defined by his past. Before he followed Christ he had persecuted believers, approved of murders, built his entire identity around a version of righteousness that he later called rubbish. And yet he made a deliberate choice to stop reaching backward and start pressing forward. The thing that happened before does not get to decide what happens next. You are not your worst moment, your biggest failure, or the version of yourself you used to be. Let it go and keep moving." },
    { v:"And I am certain that God, who began a good work within you, will continue his work until it is finally finished.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"God does not start things he does not intend to finish. The work he began in you on the day you gave your life to him is still in progress, and he has every intention of seeing it through. On the days when you feel like you are going backward, when you cannot see any growth, when it seems like nothing is changing, remember that you are not the one responsible for completing this — he started it — he is sustaining it. He will bring it all the way to the finish line." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"Anxiety always starts with the question of what you are going to get, what you are going to lose, whether there will be enough. Jesus addresses all of it with a single redirection: put the kingdom first and let everything else follow. Not because the other things do not matter but because they fall into their right place when God is in his. You will never have enough peace if you are constantly managing what belongs in God's hands — seek him first. Trust him with the rest." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord with all your heart; do not depend on your own understanding. Seek his will in all you do, and he will show you which path to take.", r:"Proverbs 3:5–6", d:"Trusting God with all your heart means releasing your grip on the outcome. It means offering him your plans, your direction, your future, and letting him do what you cannot — your own understanding is limited. It can only see what is directly in front of you. God sees the whole road, every turn, every obstacle that is coming — he is not asking you to stop thinking. He is asking you to stop treating your own reasoning as the final word. Acknowledge him in everything and he will make the path clear." },
    { v:"Commit your actions to the Lord, and your plans will succeed.", r:"Proverbs 16:3", d:"There is a difference between working hard toward a goal and clinging to the outcome with both hands — god honors diligence. He also asks you to release the results to him rather than carrying them yourself. When you commit your work to the Lord it does not mean doing less. It means doing your part with full effort and then trusting him with what comes next. The weight of controlling outcomes was never yours to carry. Give it to him and let him establish what is meant to last." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid and do not panic. For the Lord your God will personally go ahead of you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:6", d:"Moses said these words to Israel on the edge of the promised land, knowing he himself would not cross over — the task in front of them was genuinely terrifying. Giants in the land — cities with walls — enemies with armies. And God's answer to all of it was not a strategy. It was a promise: I am with you and I will not leave. Whatever you are facing today that feels too big, too overwhelming, too much, God goes with you into it — you are not walking in alone." },
    { v:"You didn't choose me. I chose you. I appointed you to go and produce lasting fruit.", r:"John 15:16", d:"You did not find God — he found you — you did not choose this path. He chose you for it before you even knew it existed — that changes the foundation of everything. Your relationship with God is not built on your pursuit of him or your consistency or your performance. It is built on the fact that he looked at you and said yes before you ever looked at him — you were appointed for this — you were placed in this season on purpose. Go and bear the fruit you were created to produce." },
    { v:"The Lord directs the steps of the godly. He delights in every detail of their lives.", r:"Psalm 37:23", d:"God is not indifferent to the details of your life. The small decisions, the ordinary days, the steps that feel insignificant, he is in all of it. He delights in watching you move when you are walking with him. That means today is not just another day to get through. It is a day that the Lord is directing if you will let him. You do not have to have it all figured out. You just have to keep walking with him and trust that he is ordering every step." },
    { v:"Look straight ahead, and fix your eyes on what lies before you.", r:"Proverbs 4:25", d:"Comparison will pull you off your path faster than almost anything else. When you are constantly looking sideways at someone else's journey, their progress, their body, their life, you stop moving forward on your own. God gave you a specific race to run. It was designed for you, calibrated to your calling, and the only way to run it well is to keep your eyes straight ahead. Stop measuring yourself against someone else's lane — run yours." },
    { v:"Take delight in the Lord, and he will give you your heart's desires.", r:"Psalm 37:4", d:"Delight is not a passive thing. It is a choice you make to find genuine joy in your relationship with God rather than treating him as a vending machine for what you want — when you truly delight in him, something shifts. Your desires begin to align with his because your heart is being shaped by his presence. The things you want start to look more like the things he wants for you. God does not ignore the desires of your heart. He transforms them into something better than what you originally asked for." },
    { v:"But those who trust in the Lord will find new strength. They will soar high on wings like eagles.", r:"Isaiah 40:31", d:"There is a kind of strength that does not come from trying harder. It comes from waiting on God, staying connected to the source, refusing to move in your own power when his power is available. The eagle does not flap furiously to stay in the air. It opens its wings and lets the current carry it — that is what God is offering you. Not just enough to survive the season but the kind of renewal that leaves you stronger than you were before it started — wait on him — do not sprint ahead of what he is doing." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Paul wrote this from a prison cell. Not from a breakthrough season or a moment of momentum — from confinement and uncertainty. What he had learned over years of hardship was that his stability did not have to depend on his circumstances — that is the strength Christ provides. Not the ability to accomplish anything you set your mind to, though that is how it gets quoted. The ability to remain steady, grounded, and at peace no matter what life hands you. That kind of strength is available to you right now, in this season, exactly as it is." },
    { v:"Give all your worries and cares to God, for he cares about you.", r:"1 Peter 5:7", d:"God is not a distant observer watching your life from a safe distance — he cares about what you are carrying. The worry about the relationship, the financial pressure, the uncertainty about what comes next, none of it is too small for his attention. He is not asking you to pretend you are not struggling. He is asking you to stop carrying the weight alone. Cast it on him — throw it — release it. He can hold what you were never designed to hold yourself." },
    { v:"This is the day the Lord has made. We will rejoice and be glad in it.", r:"Psalm 118:24", d:"Every single day is a gift, including the ones that feel difficult. The day you are in right now was made by God and it contains everything you need to walk through it with him. Not every day feels like a celebration and God does not ask you to perform joy you do not feel. But he does invite you to show up to this day with your eyes open to what he is doing in it. Something good is happening today if you are willing to look for it." },
    { v:"Don't be afraid, for I am with you. Don't be discouraged, for I am your God. I will strengthen you and help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:10", d:"Do not be afraid because I am with you — do not be discouraged because I am your God — i will strengthen you, help you, hold you up. God stacks these promises in Isaiah 41 one on top of another because he knows that fear requires more than one answer. Whatever you are afraid of right now, this is his word to you — not that the hard thing will go away — that he will be with you in it — that his hand will uphold you through it — you are not facing this alone." },
    { v:"Now all glory to God, who is able to accomplish infinitely more than we might ask or think.", r:"Ephesians 3:20", d:"Your imagination is not big enough to contain what God is capable of doing in your life. He is able to do more than you can ask, more than you can think, more than the best version of your most optimistic prayer. The limitation is not on his end — it is on yours. You have been settling for small prayers when you have access to a God who works abundantly beyond the ceiling you put on things. Bring him your biggest ask — he can handle it." },
    { v:"The Lord your God is living among you. He is a mighty savior. He will take great delight in you.", r:"Zephaniah 3:17", d:"God does not just tolerate you — he rejoices over you — he sings over you. The same God who holds the universe together looks at your life and responds with joy — not because you have it all together — not because you have earned his approval. Because you are his and that alone is enough to make him celebrate. On the days when you feel invisible, unimportant, or like you are not enough, remember this: the God of everything is singing over you right now." },
    { v:"The Lord is my shepherd; I have all that I need.", r:"Psalm 23:1", d:"The Lord is my shepherd — that single sentence carries everything. A good shepherd does not just point the sheep in a direction and walk away — he goes ahead into unknown terrain — he leads through dangerous valleys — he finds water and rest and provision. When David wrote this he was a shepherd himself — he knew what the word cost. What he was saying is that God tends to you with that same kind of attentive, personal, sacrificial care. You have everything you need because of who is leading you." },
    { v:"Taste and see that the Lord is good. Oh, the joys of those who take refuge in him!", r:"Psalm 34:8", d:"Do not just believe that God is good. Find out for yourself — taste it — experience it. There is a difference between accepting a theological truth and actually encountering God in a way that changes how you see everything. The joys of those who take refuge in him are not hypothetical. They are the testimony of people who stopped keeping their distance and came close enough to know him personally — come close. What you find there will be better than anything you were holding onto instead." },
    { v:"And we know that God causes everything to work together for the good of those who love God.", r:"Romans 8:28", d:"Nothing that is happening to you right now is outside of God's reach or outside of his purpose. The setback, the closed door, the season that made no sense and still does not. He is working all of it, not some of it — all of it. Toward something you cannot see yet from where you are standing. You do not have to understand the plan for it to be in motion. God is not waiting for your circumstances to improve before he starts doing something with them. He is already at work in the middle of the mess." },
    { v:"With man this is impossible, but with God all things are possible.", r:"Matthew 19:26", d:"There are things in your life that you have already decided are impossible — the healing that seems too far gone — the relationship that feels too broken — the door that appears permanently closed. God is asking you to take those things off your impossible list and hand them to him. What is impossible for you is not impossible for him. He is not limited by what you can see or what you can manage. He specializes in the things you have already given up on." },
    { v:"So humble yourselves under the mighty power of God, and at the right time he will lift you up in honor.", r:"1 Peter 5:6", d:"Humility is not thinking less of yourself. It is releasing the need to be in control of your own timeline. It is trusting that God's timing is better than yours, that his promotion is more lasting than the one you engineer for yourself. When you stop striving to get yourself to the place you think you deserve to be and you place yourself under his hand instead, you are positioning yourself for what only he can do. His timing is perfect — your striving is not required." },
    { v:"The Lord will work out his plans for my life — for your faithful love, O Lord, endures forever.", r:"Psalm 138:8", d:"God does not abandon his work halfway through. He does not start something in you and then lose interest. His plans for your life are not dependent on how well you have performed or how consistent you have been — his love endures — his faithfulness holds. The thing he began when he called you is still in motion, still being worked out, still heading somewhere — you are not a project he walked away from. You are the work of his hands and he finishes what he starts." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my song; he has given me victory.", r:"Exodus 15:2", d:"The Israelites sang this song standing at the edge of the Red Sea, an hour after the water closed over the Egyptian army — the strength they were celebrating was not their own. It was what God had done when there was no possible human solution left — your victory is not something you manufacture. It is something God provides when you have reached the end of your own resources and you finally stop trying to save yourself — he is your strength — he is your song." },
    { v:"Wait patiently for the Lord. Be brave and courageous. Yes, wait patiently for the Lord.", r:"Psalm 27:14", d:"Waiting on God is not the same as being passive. It is one of the most demanding things he asks of you. It requires you to hold steady when everything in you wants to force the outcome — to keep trusting when the answer has not come. To remain faithful to the process even when you cannot see the progress. Be brave enough to wait. Be courageous enough to keep believing in what you cannot yet see. God's timing has never been wrong — it will not start being wrong now." },
    { v:"He gives power to the weak and strength to the powerless.", r:"Isaiah 40:29", d:"This promise is not for people who are managing well on low reserves. It is for people who have run completely out — the faint — the powerless — the ones who have nothing left to give. If you are in that place right now, you are actually in the exact place this verse was written for. God does not ration his strength to people who still have some of their own left — he pours it into the empty ones. Let him fill what you can no longer fill yourself." },
    { v:"Be strong, and let your heart take courage, all you who wait for the Lord!", r:"Psalm 31:24", d:"Courage is not the absence of fear — it is the decision to keep going anyway. God does not ask you to not feel afraid. He asks you to be strong and let your heart take courage in the middle of the fear. And he attaches this command specifically to the people who are waiting, which means the waiting is supposed to be active. You are not just sitting around hoping things get better. You are standing firm, choosing courage, holding your ground until the Lord moves — stay strong." },
  ],
  2: [
    { v:"Thank you for making me so wonderfully complex! Your workmanship is marvelous — how well I know it.", r:"Psalm 139:14", d:"You were not made carelessly. Every part of you, the way you are built, the way your mind works, the gifts that come naturally to you and the ones you have had to fight for, all of it was intentional. God did not put you together and walk away wondering if it would work. He made you with purpose and declared the result marvelous. The way you see yourself and the way God sees you are two different things. His assessment is the accurate one — you are not an accident — you are his workmanship." },
    { v:"See how very much our Father loves us, for he calls us his children, and that is what we are!", r:"1 John 3:1", d:"Stop and actually think about what it means that God calls you his child. Not his servant, not his subject, not someone he tolerates — his child — that is not a casual word — it carries inheritance and access and belonging. You have the right to approach your Father with anything — you have his attention — you carry his name. The world may not recognize what that means but that does not make it any less true. You are loved with a specific, personal, fatherly love that has no end." },
    { v:"For we are God's masterpiece. He has created us anew in Christ Jesus, so we can do the good things he planned for us long ago.", r:"Ephesians 2:10", d:"You are not an accident and your life is not a random collection of events. You are God's masterpiece, created on purpose, placed in this specific time and season for specific reasons. The good works he prepared for you to do were not improvised — they were prepared before you were born. You are not trying to figure out if you have a purpose — you have one — you are walking into it. Keep paying attention to what God puts in front of you — it was designed for you." },
    { v:"You are altogether beautiful, my darling, beautiful in every way.", r:"Song of Solomon 4:7", d:"The one who speaks this over the Shulamite sees her completely and finds her beautiful without condition. She had already described herself as dark from working in the sun, looked down on, not measuring up to some standard. And the voice that speaks truth over her does not qualify the love or attach conditions to the acceptance. You are altogether beautiful — there is no flaw in you — that is how God speaks over you — not the version of you that has everything together. You, exactly as you are right now." },
    { v:"For you are a holy people, who belong to the Lord your God. The Lord your God has chosen you to be his own special treasure.", r:"Deuteronomy 7:6", d:"God called Israel a segullah, a personal treasure. Not because they were the most powerful nation or the most impressive people — he chose them because he wanted to — the selection was entirely his. You were not chosen because of what you brought to the table. God looked at you and said I want that one. Not because of your performance or your potential — because of his love — that is the only reason that actually holds." },
    { v:"But you are a chosen people. You are royal priests, a holy nation, God's very own possession.", r:"1 Peter 2:9", d:"Everything the world might use to define you, your social status, your background, your past, your performance, none of it is your truest identity. God has given you something better — you are chosen, royal, holy, set apart. Those are not aspirational titles. They are what you already are right now because of who claimed you. The world did not give you this identity and the world cannot take it away — walk in it — live from it. Stop letting lesser voices tell you who you are." },
    { v:"You have not received a spirit that makes you fearful slaves. Instead, you received God's Spirit when he adopted you as his own children.", r:"Romans 8:15", d:"You have not been given a spirit that makes you shrink back in fear — you have been given the Spirit of adoption. That means you can walk into the presence of God not as a stranger hoping to be tolerated but as a child who belongs there. You can call him Father because he is your Father. You can bring him your questions, your anger, your grief, your need — that kind of access was bought for you. Do not live like a servant when you have been made a son or daughter." },
    { v:"God created human beings in his own image. In the image of God he created them; male and female he created them.", r:"Genesis 1:27", d:"You were made in the image of God — that is not a metaphor or a poetic sentiment — it is a statement about what you carry. Something of the divine is woven into your nature. You were made to reflect him into the world, to create, to care, to think, to love in ways that mirror how he loves. The world will try to reduce you to what you produce or what you weigh or what you earn. God defines you by what he put inside you. You carry his image — that is who you are." },
    { v:"My old self has been crucified with Christ. It is no longer I who live, but Christ lives in me.", r:"Galatians 2:20", d:"The old version of you, the one that was driven by guilt or fear or the need to prove something, that person was crucified with Christ — what is alive now is something new. Christ living in you. That means the standard you are living by is not performance — it is presence. It is not what you can do in your own strength but what he can do through a life that is surrendered to him — you are not trying to be good enough. You already have the life of Christ in you — live from that." },
    { v:"And because you belong to him, the power of the life-giving Spirit has freed you from the power of sin that leads to death.", r:"Romans 8:2", d:"You are no longer under the law of sin and death. That means the cycle of failure, shame, trying harder, failing again does not have to be your story anymore — the Spirit of life has broken that pattern. You are operating under a new law now, one that produces what all the effort and willpower never could. The freedom Christ gives is not permission to do whatever you want. It is the actual power to become who you were always meant to be." },
    { v:"Don't copy the behavior and customs of this world, but let God transform you into a new person by changing the way you think.", r:"Romans 12:2", d:"Transformation does not come from trying harder to behave differently. It comes from allowing God to renew the way you think. Change the thinking and the behavior follows. Stop absorbing the world's definitions of success, beauty, worth, and identity and start filling your mind with what is true. The person you are becoming is being shaped by what you consistently put in front of your mind — guard your thoughts. What you feed your mind will eventually show up in how you live." },
    { v:"For God has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.", r:"2 Timothy 1:7", d:"Fear and timidity are not from God — the spirit he gave you is one of power, love, and a sound mind. That means you have the capacity to face what is in front of you. You have been given what you need to be courageous in your relationships, in your faith, in the places where life is asking you to be bold — stop shrinking back. Stop second-guessing what God put in you — the power is already there — walk in it." },
    { v:"You made all the delicate, inner parts of my body and knit me together in my mother's womb.", r:"Psalm 139:13", d:"God knit you together with intention and skill. Every part of how you are made was deliberate. The things about yourself you have never liked, the way you are wired, the body you have been given, he did not make a mistake — he was creating something specific — you were not assembled carelessly. You were woven together in the place where only God could reach, before you could do anything to earn or ruin his love. He made you on purpose and what he makes is not an accident." },
    { v:"How precious are your thoughts about me, O God. They cannot be numbered!", r:"Psalm 139:17", d:"God is thinking about you right now. Not in a general, distant way but specifically, personally, constantly. More thoughts than you could count if you tried — he is not preoccupied with bigger problems — he is not too far away to notice. He is attentive to the details of your life in a way that is almost impossible to comprehend. The God who made everything has his mind on you. That truth alone is worth sitting with longer than you usually do." },
    { v:"People judge by outward appearance, but the Lord looks at the heart.", r:"1 Samuel 16:7", d:"The world evaluates you by what is visible. Your appearance, your performance, what you produce, how you present yourself. God looks at your heart. That is not a consolation prize for people who do not have the outer things together. It is actually a more demanding standard because you cannot fake your way through it — but it is also a more generous one. God sees what no one else can reach. He sees who you actually are and he is not done working on that person yet." },
    { v:"Charm is deceptive, and beauty does not last; but a woman who fears the Lord will be greatly praised.", r:"Proverbs 31:30", d:"Charm fades — beauty is temporary. But a life rooted in the fear of the Lord produces something that does not diminish with age or change with seasons. The woman described here is not praised because of how she looks but because of the depth of character she has built over a lifetime of faithfulness — you are investing in something every day. Make sure what you are building is the kind that lasts beyond what the mirror can see." },
    { v:"She is clothed with strength and dignity, and she laughs without fear of the future.", r:"Proverbs 31:25", d:"Strength and dignity are not things you put on when you feel ready. They are what you walk in when you know who you are. The woman described here laughs at the future not because life is always good but because she is prepared, she is rooted, and she knows that God is holding what is ahead — the fear you feel about tomorrow is real. So is the strength God has placed in you to face it. You do not have to have everything figured out to walk forward with confidence." },
    { v:"For we live by believing and not by seeing.", r:"2 Corinthians 5:7", d:"Faith means moving forward before you can see the whole picture. It means trusting that God is directing your path even when the evidence is not fully visible yet. The life of faith is not a life without questions or uncertainty. It is a life where you have decided that God's word is more reliable than your circumstances. What you can see right now is not the whole story — keep walking. He sees what you cannot and he is leading you somewhere good." },
    { v:"I knew you before I formed you in your mother's womb. Before you were born I set you apart.", r:"Jeremiah 1:5", d:"Before your parents knew your name, before you took your first breath, God knew you — he did not just know about you — he knew you — personal, intimate, specific knowledge. And he called you to a purpose before you were born. That means nothing you have done or failed to do has made you too late or too disqualified for what God has set you apart to do. You were consecrated for this before you could cooperate or complicate it — your calling is older than your mistakes." },
    { v:"The Spirit of God, who raised Jesus from the dead, lives in you.", r:"Romans 8:11", d:"The same Spirit that raised Jesus from the dead lives in you — let that sink in. The most powerful event in human history was powered by the Holy Spirit, and that same Spirit has taken up residence in your body — you are not running on your own strength. You have access to resurrection power — that changes what is possible for you. Whatever feels dead in your life right now, a dream, a relationship, a sense of purpose, do not write it off — you carry the power of the resurrection." },
    { v:"And I am convinced that nothing can ever separate us from God's love.", r:"Romans 8:38", d:"Make a list of everything that could possibly come between you and God's love — death — suffering — the future. Powers you cannot see — your own failure. Paul walked through the whole list and came to the same conclusion every time: none of it is strong enough. Nothing has the power to cut you off from the love of God. You cannot fall so far that his love cannot reach you — you cannot fail so badly that it runs out. His love for you is not conditional on your condition." },
    { v:"Even before he made the world, God loved us and chose us in Christ to be holy and without fault in his eyes.", r:"Ephesians 1:4", d:"Before the world was made, God had already chosen you — that is not a casual statement. It means his love for you did not begin when you got it together or when you finally started pursuing him — it began before you existed — before creation. You were loved before you had any capacity to earn or lose that love. What God chose before time started cannot be undone by what happens inside of it — you were his before you were anything else." },
    { v:"So now there is no condemnation for those who belong to Christ Jesus.", r:"Romans 8:1", d:"There is no condemnation for you in Christ Jesus. Not some condemnation that you have to manage carefully — not condemnation waiting for your next failure — none. The verdict has been rendered and it is not guilty. That means the voice that keeps telling you that you are not forgiven, that you have gone too far, that God is disappointed in you, that voice is lying. The sentence was lifted when Christ paid it — you are free — walk like it." },
    { v:"Your real life is hidden with Christ in God.", r:"Colossians 3:3", d:"Your real life is not what other people can see. It is not your accomplishments or your appearance or your social presence. It is hidden with Christ in God, stored in the safest possible place. That means nothing the world can do to your visible life can touch your actual life. Opinions cannot reach it — failures cannot destroy it. Losses cannot take it from you — you are more secure than you feel. The most important thing about you is held by the one thing that cannot be moved." },
    { v:"We are citizens of heaven, where the Lord Jesus Christ lives.", r:"Philippians 3:20", d:"You are a citizen of heaven — that is not a future status — it is your present reality. You live in this world but you do not ultimately belong to it. Its values, its measures of success, its definition of who matters, none of it is your final standard. You answer to a different kingdom with a different King. That means you are free from the pressure to perform for an audience that was never supposed to define you. Live for the one whose opinion is the only one that actually counts." },
    { v:"God saved us and called us to live a holy life — not because we deserved it, but because that was his plan.", r:"2 Timothy 1:9", d:"God did not save you because of anything you did. He saved you and called you according to his own purpose and grace, and that grace was given to you in Christ before time began — you did not earn your way into this. You cannot lose your way out of it by your own failure — your calling is not contingent on your track record. It is rooted in the unchanging character and sovereign grace of the God who called you before you were capable of responding." },
    { v:"Search me, O God, and know my heart; test me and know my anxious thoughts.", r:"Psalm 139:23", d:"It takes more courage to invite God's examination than almost anything else. Because he does not look at the surface — he looks at everything — the motives underneath the good behavior — the fears driving the ambition — the wounds shaping the patterns. Inviting God into that level of intimacy requires trust that he will handle what he finds with love rather than condemnation — he will — he already knows it all. What you are doing in this prayer is giving him permission to deal with what you cannot fix yourself." },
    { v:"Point out anything in me that offends you, and lead me along the path of everlasting life.", r:"Psalm 139:24", d:"The paths that lead to pain are not always obviously wrong. Sometimes they are the paths of familiar habits, comfortable compromises, quiet resentments that have been allowed to stay too long. God can see the destination of roads you are currently on. When you ask him to reveal any grievous way in you, you are inviting him to redirect you before the road takes you somewhere you do not want to go — that is not a prayer of self-condemnation — it is a prayer of trust." },
  ],
  3: [
    { v:"Create in me a clean heart, O God. Renew a loyal spirit within me.", r:"Psalm 51:10", d:"David wrote this after the worst failure of his life — not a small sin. A sequence of devastating choices that cost another man his life. And what he asked for was not improvement or a second chance to be better — he asked God to create something entirely new. The same word used when God made the world from nothing. Some things cannot be fixed — they have to be made new. Whatever the state of your heart today, that is exactly the kind of work God specializes in." },
    { v:"Though our bodies are dying, our spirits are being renewed every day.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:16", d:"Your outer life is wearing down — that is just true. Bodies age, energy fades, things break and do not come back the way they were. But while that is happening, God is doing something on the inside that goes in the opposite direction — renewal — daily. Not occasional, not when you feel spiritual enough to access it — every day. Whatever is diminishing on the outside is not the final word. The most important part of you is being strengthened by God himself, one day at a time." },
    { v:"The Holy Spirit produces this kind of fruit in our lives: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control.", r:"Galatians 5:22–23", d:"The fruit of the Spirit is not a checklist of virtues to acquire through discipline. It is the natural overflow of a life connected to the source. You do not produce love and joy and peace by trying harder — you produce them by staying close to God. A branch connected to the vine does not strain to make fruit — it simply stays connected and fruit happens. The question is not how hard you are working at being better — it is how closely you are abiding in him." },
    { v:"For you know that when your faith is tested, your endurance has a chance to grow.", r:"James 1:3", d:"The testing of your faith is not God being careless with you. It is God developing something in you that comfort and ease never could. Endurance does not come from the easy seasons. It is built in the ones where you had every reason to quit and you did not. Every hard thing you are walking through right now is working on your rootedness — the pressure is not punishing you. It is producing something in you that will hold when everything else is shaking." },
    { v:"So let it grow, for when your endurance is fully developed, you will be perfect and complete, needing nothing.", r:"James 1:4", d:"Do not cut the process short — that is the whole point of this verse. The endurance God is building in you has a full effect and that full effect requires time. It requires you to stay in the hard thing longer than feels necessary. Cutting out early produces something incomplete, a faith that looks solid but has not been tested deep enough to hold under real pressure — stay in it. Let God finish what he started. The completeness he is working toward is worth the wait." },
    { v:"No discipline is enjoyable while it is happening — it's painful! But afterward there will be a peaceful harvest of right living.", r:"Hebrews 12:11", d:"Discipline does not feel good while it is happening — it just does not. God is not asking you to pretend otherwise. But afterward, it produces something you cannot get any other way: the fruit of righteousness — the peace that comes from having been trained — the strength that comes from having been pressed. Every hard season, every correction, every moment where God is refining something in you is working toward a harvest. The discomfort is not the destination — it is the process." },
    { v:"Plant the good seeds of righteousness, and you will harvest a crop of love.", r:"Hosea 10:12", d:"Fallow ground is not bad ground — it is ground that has been left unworked. It has closed over and hardened because nothing has been planted in it. God is asking you to break it up. To stop leaving whole areas of your life untended, whole parts of your heart uncultivated. The harvest of righteousness and love that he promises comes from the ground that has been prepared. What in your life has been left fallow that God is asking you to tend?." },
    { v:"Work hard to show the results of your salvation, obeying God with deep reverence and fear.", r:"Philippians 2:12", d:"Work out what God has already worked in. Salvation is not the end — it is the beginning of a process of becoming. The fear and trembling Paul describes is not anxiety about losing your salvation. It is the appropriate reverence of someone who understands the magnitude of what they are carrying — you are holding something of extraordinary value. Handle it with the seriousness it deserves. Let the life of Christ in you show up in the way you actually live." },
    { v:"For God is working in you, giving you the desire and the power to do what pleases him.", r:"Philippians 2:13", d:"God is not just watching from a distance to see if you manage to do the right thing. He is actively working in you, producing the desire to do what pleases him and giving you the power to follow through. That means when you feel a pull toward obedience, toward generosity, toward patience you do not naturally have, that is God at work — you are not generating this on your own. Cooperate with what he is already doing in you." },
    { v:"When troubles come your way, consider it an opportunity for great joy.", r:"James 1:2", d:"Trials are not interruptions to the life God has for you — they are part of it. When you encounter trouble, James says consider it joy, not because you enjoy suffering but because you know what suffering is producing. You have knowledge the person without faith does not have. You know that this is not the end of the story. You know that God is working in the middle of this — that knowledge changes everything. Hardship does not have the final word — god does." },
    { v:"If you need wisdom, ask our generous God, and he will give it to you. He will not rebuke you for asking.", r:"James 1:5", d:"God is not annoyed by your need for wisdom. He is not withholding it until you prove you can manage without it — ask him. He gives generously, without finding fault, without making you feel embarrassed for not already knowing — that is a remarkable invitation. In every situation where you genuinely do not know what to do, there is a direct line to the one who does — use it. You do not have to figure everything out on your own." },
    { v:"I have hidden your word in my heart, that I might not sin against you.", r:"Psalm 119:11", d:"The Word of God stored in your heart is not just information. It is a living resource that works in you even when you are not consciously accessing it. When the moment of temptation comes, when the pressure hits, when your emotions are pulling you in a direction your convictions know is wrong, what you have hidden in your heart speaks up. Scripture memorized is Scripture available at the moment you need it most. What are you building into yourself for the moments that matter?." },
    { v:"Your word is a lamp to guide my feet and a light for my path.", r:"Psalm 119:105", d:"God does not always give you the full map — he gives you enough light for the next step. That can be frustrating when you want to see the whole route before you move. But the lamp he provides is calibrated to what you actually need: light for your feet right now, direction for the path directly ahead. Trust the light you have. Take the step in front of you. More light will come as you move. He does not leave you without what you need to keep going." },
    { v:"Since we are living by the Spirit, let us follow the Spirit's leading in every part of our lives.", r:"Galatians 5:25", d:"Living by the Spirit is not a passive experience. It requires you to stay aligned with what the Spirit is doing, to keep pace with where he is leading, to choose his direction over yours when they diverge — the Spirit is moving. The question is whether you are moving with him or insisting on your own direction. Every day is a fresh opportunity to say yes to what he is doing and no to what he is not. That is what walking by the Spirit actually looks like." },
    { v:"Let us not neglect our meeting together, as some people do, but encourage one another.", r:"Hebrews 10:25", d:"You were not designed to do life alone. The encouragement that comes from being with other believers is not optional — it is part of how God built the system. You need people who will speak truth into your life, who will hold you accountable, who will remind you who you are when you forget — and someone else needs that from you. Do not let isolation convince you that you can sustain your faith in a vacuum. Show up for community — it matters more than you think." },
    { v:"Keep putting into practice all you learned and received. Then the God of peace will be with you.", r:"Philippians 4:9", d:"Faith is not primarily theoretical. It shows up in practice, in what you actually do with your body and your time and your choices. Paul says put it into practice, not just believe it or discuss it. What you have learned about God, about how to live, about what matters, start doing those things — repeatedly. Until they become the way you actually live rather than the way you think you should live. Practice is where belief becomes real." },
    { v:"Let your roots grow down into him, and let your lives be built on him. Then your faith will grow strong.", r:"Colossians 2:7", d:"Roots grown deep do not happen overnight. They are built through time, through consistency, through seasons where the only thing happening is quiet growth beneath the surface. The overflow of thanksgiving that Paul describes here is not manufactured. It is what comes out of a life that has been slowly, steadily rooted in Christ over time. Keep showing up to your faith even in the unglamorous seasons. The roots are growing even when you cannot see them." },
    { v:"This same God who takes care of me will supply all your needs from his glorious riches.", r:"Philippians 4:19", d:"God does not supply your needs out of a limited reserve that might run out. He supplies them from the infinite riches of his glory. That means the measure of his provision is not your need — it is his abundance. He is not rationing what he gives you based on what he has left — he has everything — he gives from that place. Whatever you are lacking today, bring it to the God whose resources have no ceiling and whose generosity has no end." },
    { v:"Think clearly and exercise self-control. Look forward to the gracious salvation that will come to you.", r:"1 Peter 1:13", d:"The mind prepared for action is not the mind that wanders through the day reacting to whatever comes at it. It is the mind that is focused, intentional, and set on what is true. Self-control starts in the mind, not in behavior. Before you can live with discipline in your body, your relationships, and your choices, you have to get your thinking straight. Fix your hope on what God has promised. That is the anchor that keeps everything else from drifting." },
    { v:"Warn each other every day, while it is still today, so that none of you will be deceived by sin and hardened against God.", r:"Hebrews 3:13", d:"Hardness of heart does not happen all at once. It happens slowly, one small unaddressed compromise at a time. One decision that should have been brought to God but was not. One area of life that was closed off from his access. The antidote is daily encouragement, daily accountability, daily honesty about where you are. Do not wait until you are far down a wrong road to start being honest. Stay close to people who will speak truth into your life today." },
    { v:"We are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:18", d:"Transformation happens through sustained attention. When you consistently spend time looking at who God is, in his Word, in prayer, in worship, something changes in you — not immediately, not dramatically every day, but gradually. You start to look more like the one you are looking at — you cannot think your way into godliness — you cannot willpower yourself into it. But you can position yourself in his presence, consistently, and let the looking do its slow work." },
    { v:"Those who live to please the Spirit will harvest everlasting life.", r:"Galatians 6:8", d:"You are always planting something. Every choice, every habit, every thing you consistently feed your mind and your body is a seed. The harvest is coming whether you planned for it or not — what are you sowing right now?. — what are you filling your hours with?. What are you building with the small decisions no one else sees?. The crop you will stand in months from now is being planted today. Plant what you actually want to harvest." },
    { v:"So let's not get tired of doing what is good. At just the right time we will reap a harvest of blessing if we don't give up.", r:"Galatians 6:9", d:"The harvest does not come on your schedule. It comes at the appointed time for that particular seed. That is the season you are in right now if everything is right and nothing is showing yet — you have been doing the work — you have been faithful in the small things — the harvest is not late — it is coming at exactly the right time — do not quit before it arrives. The only way to not reap is to stop sowing before the season turns — keep going." },
    { v:"Just as you accepted Christ Jesus as your Lord, you must continue to follow him.", r:"Colossians 2:6", d:"The same posture that brought you to faith in Christ is the posture that sustains it. You did not come to him demanding terms or negotiating the conditions. You came open-handed and you received — that is how you continue. Not striving for a higher level of spiritual achievement but staying in the position of receiving, of trusting, of walking with him the way you walked toward him at the beginning. Faith is not a phase — it is the whole way of life." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Whatever you are doing today, you have a choice about who you are doing it for. When you work as if God is watching, and he is, the quality of your effort does not depend on whether anyone else notices or whether you are being recognized or rewarded. The standard is steady because the audience does not change. That brings a freedom that recognition from people can never provide — do your work well. Not for the applause but for the one who sees everything." },
    { v:"God blesses those who patiently endure testing and temptation.", r:"James 1:12", d:"The blessing at the end of the trial is not automatic. It belongs to those who remain steadfast through it, who do not walk away from their faith when the pressure increases — you are being tested right now. Not to fail you but to reveal and develop something in you that could not be produced any other way — stand firm. The crown of life is not given to the ones who had the easiest road. It is given to the ones who stayed faithful on the hard one." },
    { v:"Don't just listen to God's word. You must do what it says.", r:"James 1:22", d:"Hearing the Word without doing it is a form of self-deception. You walk away thinking you have engaged with God when really you have only processed information — the doing is where faith becomes real. It is easy to nod along with truth in a comfortable setting. It is harder to actually live it when it costs something. What have you been hearing that you have not yet done?. The gap between knowing and doing is exactly where obedience lives." },
    { v:"Don't reject the Lord's discipline, and don't be upset when he corrects you. For the Lord corrects those he loves.", r:"Proverbs 3:11–12", d:"God's correction is not rejection — it is the opposite. A father who does not discipline is a father who does not care. When God allows difficulty, correction, or the natural consequences of wrong choices to enter your life, it is because he loves you too much to let you stay where you are. The rebuke of the Lord is proof of the relationship, not evidence of its absence — he is invested in who you are becoming — that is why he does not leave you unchanged." },
    { v:"Joyful are those who obey his laws and search for him with all their hearts.", r:"Psalm 119:2", d:"Seeking God with your whole heart means he gets all of you, not just the parts you are comfortable giving. It means bringing your doubts and your failures and your hardest questions into his presence, not just your praise. Half-hearted seeking produces half-hearted results. When you go after God with everything you have, you find him — that is not a formula — it is a promise — he is not hiding. He is waiting for you to pursue him like he is actually worth finding." },
    { v:"Be strong and immovable. Always work enthusiastically for the Lord, for nothing you do for the Lord is ever useless.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:58", d:"Because of the resurrection, nothing you do for the Lord is wasted. Not a single act of faithfulness, not a single prayer, not a single day you chose to keep going when quitting would have been easier — the resurrection means this life matters. What you build here, how you love, how you serve, how you remain steadfast in the hard seasons, all of it carries eternal weight — be immovable — keep working. None of it is in vain." },
    { v:"After you have suffered a little while, he will restore, support, and strengthen you, and place you on a firm foundation.", r:"1 Peter 5:10", d:"The suffering is real. Peter does not minimize it — but he gives it a timeframe: a little while — and he gives it an outcome: restoration, strength, establishment. God himself will do this — not you, through your recovery and resilience — him. After you have gone through the hard thing, he will personally come in and rebuild what the season took — hold on. What God builds on the other side of suffering is stronger than what was there before." },
  ],
  4: [
    { v:"He is not here! He is risen from the dead, just as he said would happen.", r:"Matthew 28:6", d:"He is not here — he is risen — the tomb is empty and that changes everything. Not just as a theological statement but as a present reality in your life. The same Jesus who walked out of the grave is the Jesus who walks with you today. Death could not hold him. That means the things in your life that look dead, the dream that seems over, the situation that looks finished, do not write them off — you serve a God who specializes in resurrection. What he walks out of the grave with is never the same as what went in." },
    { v:"We are pressed on every side by troubles, but we are not crushed. We are perplexed, but not driven to despair.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:8", d:"Pressed but not crushed, perplexed but not in despair — there is a limit on how far trouble can take you when God is with you — it can press you but it cannot crush you. It can confuse you but it cannot destroy your hope — you are not indestructible but you are held. The pressure is real and so is the boundary around how far it goes. God has set a limit on what your circumstances can do to your soul. Stay in him and you will bend without breaking." },
    { v:"We get knocked down, but we are not destroyed.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:9", d:"Knocked down is not knocked out — there is a difference — you can get up from knocked down. People have written you off before and been wrong. Circumstances have seemed final before and turned. You carry something that cannot be destroyed by opposition or failure or loss. The life of God in you is not extinguishable — get back up. Whatever round you feel like you are in, you are still standing — that alone means something — do not stay down." },
    { v:"I want to know Christ and experience the mighty power that raised him from the dead.", r:"Philippians 3:10", d:"Paul wanted to know the power of the resurrection and the fellowship of Christ's sufferings in the same breath. He did not separate them into a desirable and an undesirable — he understood that they come together. The depth of what God can do through your life is connected to the depth of what you are willing to walk through with him. You cannot have resurrection power without being willing to go through the places where you need it." },
    { v:"Our bodies are buried in weakness, but they will be raised in strength.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:43", d:"What goes in the ground and what comes out are not the same thing. The seed that is buried does not give you a preview of the plant. The body that is sown in weakness is raised in power. What you are investing in your life right now, the discipline, the faithfulness, the consistency in the unseen seasons, does not look like the harvest it is producing. Do not judge the outcome by the current state of what has been planted. God transforms what is buried." },
    { v:"Thanks be to God! He gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:57", d:"The victory has already been won — you are not fighting toward it — you are fighting from it. That changes everything about how you engage with the hard things in your life. You are not trying to get to a place of victory. You are already there, in Christ, and everything you face is being faced from that position. The enemy does not have the final word — god does — and his final word is victory through Jesus Christ." },
    { v:"No, in all these things we are more than conquerors through him who loved us.", r:"Romans 8:37", d:"More than conquerors — not barely surviving. Not getting through by the skin of your teeth — more than. Paul coined a word that means overwhelming victory. And the source of it is through him who loved us. Not through your own endurance or willpower or perfect faith. Through the love of Christ — you are not just enduring this season. You are overcoming it — that is who you are in him." },
    { v:"Because of our faith, Christ has brought us into this place of undeserved privilege where we now stand.", r:"Romans 5:2", d:"You have access. Right now, in your current state, with everything you have done and everything you have not done. Access to the grace of God — not access to apply for access — not access to the waiting room — you are already in. Paul says we stand here — present tense. You are already standing in the grace of God — not working your way toward it — not hoping you eventually make it — standing in it. Let that be your footing today." },
    { v:"We can rejoice when we run into problems and trials, for we know that they help us develop endurance.", r:"Romans 5:3", d:"Rejoicing in suffering is not pretending that hard things do not hurt. It is choosing to hold two things at once: the real pain of the situation and the real knowledge of what God does with it. The suffering is not the end of the story — it is the beginning of a process — endurance — character — hope — that sequence is not automatic. It starts with a choice to keep trusting when trusting is the hardest thing — make that choice today." },
    { v:"And endurance develops strength of character, and character strengthens our confident hope of salvation.", r:"Romans 5:4", d:"The hope that comes at the end of this chain is not wishful thinking — it is the product of a proven process. You went through the suffering — you developed endurance — you built character. And character, tested and real, produces hope that does not disappoint because it is not built on circumstances. It is built on who God has proven himself to be in the middle of your hardest seasons — that is the most solid foundation hope can have." },
    { v:"And this hope will not lead to disappointment. For we know how dearly God loves us.", r:"Romans 5:5", d:"Hope rooted in God does not disappoint because it is not built on outcomes. It is built on the Holy Spirit poured into your heart. The love of God is not a distant concept — it has been deposited inside you. That means your hope has an internal anchor that is not moved by what is happening externally — your circumstances may be uncertain — your feelings may fluctuate. But the love of God poured into your heart does not change with any of it — that is what your hope stands on." },
    { v:"I pray that God, the source of hope, will fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"God is the source of hope, not just a supporter of it. When hope feels thin or distant, you do not manufacture more of it by trying harder — you go to the source. You ask him to fill you with joy and peace in the believing, and then the Holy Spirit produces an overflow of hope in you that exceeds what your situation seems to allow — you cannot produce hope from the inside out. Let God produce it from the outside in." },
    { v:"Let all that I am wait quietly before God, for my hope is in him.", r:"Psalm 62:5", d:"Be still and wait. Not because there is nothing you could do but because waiting on God in silence is its own kind of strength. The soul that is constantly moving, constantly trying to solve, constantly filling the silence with noise, never gets to the place where it can actually hear what God is saying — your hope comes from him. Stop looking everywhere else for it — get quiet — wait — he will meet you in the stillness." },
    { v:"He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress where I will not be shaken.", r:"Psalm 62:6", d:"There is a difference between the things that shake and the things that hold. Most of what you can see and touch will shake at some point — relationships — finances — health — plans. But God as your rock and fortress does not move when everything else does — he does not shake with your circumstances. When you build your stability on him rather than on the things around you, you stop being undone every time something shifts — he holds when nothing else does." },
    { v:"Why am I discouraged? Why is my heart so sad? I will put my hope in God!", r:"Psalm 42:11", d:"The Psalmist asks himself why he is downcast and then answers his own question with truth — that is a skill worth developing. Your emotions are real but they are not always reliable reporters of reality — when your soul is discouraged, speak truth to it. Put your hope in God. Tell yourself what you know to be true rather than letting your feelings have the final word. Feelings are not the enemy. They just need to be held up against what is actually true." },
    { v:"O Lord, you alone are my hope. I've trusted you, O Lord, from childhood.", r:"Psalm 71:5", d:"Hope in God is not something you arrive at after you have exhausted every other option — it is the first place you go. The Psalmist says God alone is his hope, and he has been trusting him since childhood — that kind of hope is not fragile — it has been tested over a lifetime. Whatever season of life you are in right now, God is worthy of your trust — he has been faithful before — he will be faithful again. His track record gives you every reason to keep hoping." },
    { v:"I will keep on hoping for your help; I will praise you more and more.", r:"Psalm 71:14", d:"But I will hope continually and will praise you yet more and more. The word continually is tamid, always, without stopping — not when things improve — not when he feels it — continually. The more and more is not conditioned on a good week. It is a commitment that escalates regardless of the situation it is made in." },
    { v:"The Lord is good to those who depend on him, to those who search for him.", r:"Lamentations 3:25", d:"The Lord is good to those who wait for him. Jeremiah writes this from the wreckage of a destroyed city — he is not writing from a comfortable place. He is choosing to hold onto one true thing in the middle of catastrophe. And that thing is that God is good, specifically to those who seek him and wait for him — your waiting is not going unnoticed — your seeking is landing somewhere. God is good to you right now in this hard season whether or not it feels like it." },
    { v:"So it is good to wait quietly for salvation from the Lord.", r:"Lamentations 3:26", d:"Waiting quietly for salvation from the Lord is not resignation. It is one of the most active spiritual postures there is. It requires you to hold your ground against despair, to refuse the temptation of rushing ahead of God, and to trust that what he is doing in the silence is better than what you could manufacture in the noise. The quiet waiting takes courage — it is not passivity — it is trust in its most concentrated form." },
    { v:"Our present troubles are small and won't last very long. Yet they produce for us a glory that vastly outweighs them.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:17", d:"Light and momentary. That is how Paul describes the troubles he was experiencing, troubles that included imprisonment, beatings, and constant danger — he was not minimizing them — he was comparing them. Against the weight of eternal glory, every hard thing in this life becomes proportionally smaller. You are not being asked to pretend your pain is nothing. You are being invited to hold it next to something so much larger that it changes how the pain sits." },
    { v:"We fix our gaze on things that cannot be seen. For the things we see now will soon be gone, but the things we cannot see will last forever.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:18", d:"What you can see is temporary — what you cannot see is eternal — that is not a spiritual platitude — it is a reorientation of what is actually real. The invisible things, God's promises, his presence, his purposes, his eternal glory, are more real and more lasting than anything you can currently see or touch — fix your eyes there. Not because the visible things do not matter but because they are not the truest or most permanent things in your life." },
    { v:"Always be full of joy in the Lord. I say it again — rejoice!", r:"Philippians 4:4", d:"Rejoice always — not when things go well — not when you feel like it — always. Paul was in prison when he wrote this. He was not telling you to perform happiness you do not feel. He was pointing to a joy that is not dependent on circumstances, a joy rooted in who God is and what he has done, that can be accessed regardless of what is happening around you. The joy of the Lord is not a mood — it is a posture — choose it today." },
    { v:"I have told you all this so that you may have peace in me. Take heart, because I have overcome the world.", r:"John 16:33", d:"Jesus did not promise that following him would make life easy. He promised that in the middle of the hard life, you would not face it alone. The peace he offers is not the absence of trouble. It is the presence of someone who has already overcome every trouble you will ever face. He says take heart not because the difficulty goes away but because the one who has conquered it all is with you in it. You are not fighting a battle he has not already won." },
    { v:"For I am convinced that neither death nor life, neither angels nor demons, neither the present nor the future, nor any powers, neither height nor depth, nor anything else in all creation, will be able to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord.", r:"Romans 8:38-39", d:"Nothing can separate you from the love of God — death cannot — life cannot — your worst day cannot — your biggest failure cannot. Powers you can see and powers you cannot see. Things that happened in the past and things that will happen in the future. Paul went through the whole list and came to the same conclusion every time. There is no version of your life in which God's love runs out — you cannot get outside of it. It holds you on your worst day the same as your best." },
    { v:"For every child of God defeats this evil world, and we achieve this victory through our faith.", r:"1 John 5:4", d:"The victory is not something you achieve. It is something you carry because of who you belong to. Every child of God overcomes the world. Not by being stronger or smarter or more disciplined — by faith. By the living reality of the Spirit in you that is greater than everything aligned against you — you are not waiting to become an overcomer — you already are one. Walk in what has already been given to you." },
    { v:"The Spirit who lives in you is greater than the spirit who lives in the world.", r:"1 John 4:4", d:"The Spirit living in you is greater than anything you are up against. Greater than the lies that have been spoken over you. Greater than the opposition you are facing. Greater than the patterns you have been trying to break for years. You are not fighting this battle with your own strength. The one who lives in you has already overcome the one working against you — you are on the winning side of this fight — do not let the enemy convince you otherwise." },
    { v:"For I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worth comparing with the glory that is to be revealed to us.", r:"Romans 8:18", d:"What you are going through right now is real — the pain, the difficulty, the cost of it. None of that is being minimized. But Paul says there is a glory coming that is not even in the same category as the present suffering. The comparison cannot be made because they are not equal. You are in a temporary chapter of a story that ends in something so good it makes the hard chapters look different in retrospect — keep going — the ending God has written is worth it." },
    { v:"I thank my God in all my remembrance of you, always in every prayer of mine for you all making my prayer with joy, because of your partnership in the gospel from the first day until now.", r:"Philippians 1:3-5", d:"Gratitude is not just a feeling — it is a practice. Paul was in prison when he wrote this and his first move was to thank God for the people in his life. He was not waiting for good circumstances to be grateful. He was choosing gratitude as a way of engaging with his life, even the parts of it that were hard. Find the people in your life today who are worth thanking God for. Let that be where your mind goes instead of the list of what is lacking." },
    { v:"The Lord is my light and my salvation — so why should I be afraid?", r:"Psalm 27:1", d:"The Lord is your light. He illuminates what is actually true when fear is trying to distort everything — he is your salvation. The thing you are afraid of losing cannot take your real life from you — he is the stronghold of your life. The place you run to when everything else is shaking. When you know who your light, your salvation, and your stronghold actually is, the question of whom you should be afraid of answers itself — you have nothing to fear." },
    { v:"Everything written in the Scriptures was written to teach us, so that we might have hope.", r:"Romans 15:4", d:"The stories in Scripture were not written to give you historical information — they were written to give you hope. Every account of God's faithfulness to his people in the middle of impossible circumstances was preserved so that you could read it and know: he does this — he shows up — he delivers — he keeps his word. When your own story feels uncertain, you have thousands of years of evidence that God's word holds — that is why you can have endurance — that is why you can have hope." },
  ],
  5: [
    { v:"This is my command — be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid or discouraged. For the Lord your God is with you wherever you go.", r:"Joshua 1:9", d:"God does not ask you to be brave because the situation is not actually dangerous. He asks you to be brave because he is going with you into it — the courage he commands is not confidence in yourself. It is confidence in the one who goes before you, who stands beside you, who will not abandon you no matter how hard it gets. Whatever you are facing today, you are not walking into it alone. That is the only reason you need to take the next step." },
    { v:"Be on guard. Stand firm in the faith. Be courageous. Be strong.", r:"1 Corinthians 16:13", d:"Stand firm — be courageous — be strong. There is nothing soft about the faith God is calling you to. It requires vigilance, decisiveness, and the willingness to hold your ground when everything around you is shifting — the world is not neutral. It is constantly pulling you toward compromise, toward comfort, toward the path of least resistance. Fighting that current is not easy — it requires a particular kind of courage — but you were not made for the easy path — you were made for this one." },
    { v:"Who is like you, O Lord, among the gods? Who is like you, majestic in holiness, awesome in glorious deeds, doing wonders?", r:"Exodus 15:11", d:"Who is like you, Lord?. The question is not really a question — it is a declaration — there is no one and nothing like him. The God you serve is in a category entirely by himself. His power, his holiness, his faithfulness, his love. There is no rival, no comparison, no force in heaven or on earth that stands in the same place. When fear tells you that what you are facing is bigger than your God, bring it back to this: who is like him?. — nobody — he is incomparable." },
    { v:"Be strong in the Lord and in his mighty power.", r:"Ephesians 6:10", d:"The strength God calls you to is not strength you generate on your own — it is strength you draw from him — his mighty power. That means you do not have to have everything in you before you step into what he is calling you to. You step in with what you have and draw on what is his — that is how the Christian life works — not your capacity plus God's help. His capacity working through your availability. Be strong in the Lord — not in yourself." },
    { v:"God is our refuge and strength, always ready to help in times of trouble.", r:"Psalm 46:1", d:"God is not available to help when you have done enough to deserve it — he is always ready to help — that is the word here — a very present help — not a help you have to earn access to. Not a help on standby waiting for the right spiritual conditions — present — now — in this trouble you are in right now. You do not have to get yourself together before you go to him. You go to him in the middle of the mess and he is already there." },
    { v:"The Lord gives his people strength. The Lord blesses them with peace.", r:"Psalm 29:11", d:"The God who speaks with enough power to break cedars and shake the wilderness is the same God who turns toward his people and gives them strength and peace — the power is immense. And it is directed at you in the form of provision and peace — that is the character of the God you serve. Overwhelming in power and tender toward his people — both — at the same time. Today he is giving strength and peace to those who are his — receive it." },
    { v:"My health may fail, and my spirit may grow weak, but God remains the strength of my heart.", r:"Psalm 73:26", d:"Asaph wrote this after confessing that he had nearly lost his faith completely. He was envious of the wicked who prospered while he suffered for following God. And at the end of that crisis, this is what he landed on: everything else may fail, but God is the strength of my heart and my portion forever — not an argument that nothing will fail. But the assurance that what holds when everything fails is God himself — he is enough even when everything else runs out." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my shield. I trust him with all my heart.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"God is both your strength and your shield — offense and defense. The power to face what is ahead and the protection from what would destroy you. Trust is the hinge between the two. When your heart trusts him, the help comes, the exulting follows, and the gratitude overflows into song — the sequence is not accidental. Trust is where it starts. Everything else is downstream of choosing to lean your full weight on him." },
    { v:"Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest.", r:"Matthew 11:28", d:"Jesus issues this invitation to the exhausted — not the spiritually prepared. The ones who are loaded down and running on empty. He does not say get yourself together and then come. He says come as you are, exactly as you are, and I will give you rest — not a plan for rest — not advice on how to find rest — he gives it. Whatever you are carrying right now that was never yours to carry, he is asking you to bring it and put it down — come to him." },
    { v:"Even youths shall faint and be weary, and young men shall fall exhausted; but they who wait for the Lord shall renew their strength.", r:"Isaiah 40:30-31", d:"Even people at the peak of their physical strength run out eventually. Youth and capability have a ceiling. But the strength that comes from waiting on the Lord does not have one — it is renewed — again. Each time it is needed. The eagle soars not by flapping harder but by catching what is already rising. You are not meant to sustain this on your own effort. Stay connected to the source and let what is already in motion carry you higher than your own strength could take you." },
    { v:"For I hold you by your right hand — I, the Lord your God. And I say to you, Don't be afraid. I am here to help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:13", d:"God says he is holding your right hand — not standing nearby, available if you ask — holding — there is physical intimacy in that image — a grip — a deliberate act of contact. Do not be afraid because I, specifically I, am the one holding you. Whatever you are walking through today, he has you by the hand. Not a distant God managing your situation from a safe distance. The God of everything, gripping your hand and walking with you through it." },
    { v:"The Sovereign Lord is my strength! He makes me as surefooted as a deer, able to tread upon the heights.", r:"Habakkuk 3:19", d:"Habakkuk prays this after God tells him that Jerusalem will be destroyed by Babylon — habakkuk trembles — the fig tree will not blossom — the fields will produce no food — the flocks will be cut off. And in the middle of announcing all of that, he declares that the Lord is his strength and gives him the feet of a deer for high places — not removed from the difficult terrain. Equipped to stand on it. Whatever impossible ground you are being asked to navigate, God will make you capable of it." },
    { v:"Through God we will do valiantly, and it is he who shall tread down our foes.", r:"Psalm 60:12", d:"With God we will do valiantly — that is not a prediction — it is a declaration — the bravery is ours to bring — the victory is his to give. They are not the same thing and they are not in competition with each other. God does not do your part while you watch. And you do not win on your own while he observes. You bring your courage and your effort and he brings his power — together — that is the partnership he is offering. Show up with everything you have and trust him with the rest." },
    { v:"The steadfast love of the Lord never ceases; his mercies never come to an end; they are new every morning; great is your faithfulness.", r:"Lamentations 3:22-23", d:"Every morning you wake up, God's mercies are new — not recycled from yesterday — new — he does not run out. He does not get tired of being faithful to you. Whatever mistakes yesterday held, whatever you failed to do or did that you should not have, this morning is a clean start. The steadfast love of the Lord is not contingent on what you did last night — it is new this morning — receive it. Start today from that place." },
    { v:"My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.", r:"2 Corinthians 12:9", d:"God's power is not made available despite your weakness — it is made available through it. Your weakness is not an obstacle to what God wants to do in your life. It is the exact condition that makes his power most visible. When you are strong enough on your own, it is hard to tell where your strength ends and his begins. When you run out, what sustains you is unmistakably him. Stop apologizing for your weakness. Let it be the place where his power shows up." },
    { v:"For we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses, but one who in every respect has been tempted as we are, yet without sin.", r:"Hebrews 4:15", d:"Jesus is not a high priest who looks at your struggle from a comfortable distance — he was tempted in every way you are. He knows what it is to be tired, to be lonely, to be misunderstood, to feel the weight of what is being asked of him. He is not judging your weakness from the outside — he understands it from the inside. That means when you come to him with the parts of you that are struggling, you are not coming to someone who will be surprised — you are coming to someone who already knows." },
    { v:"With your help I can advance against a troop; with my God I can scale a wall.", r:"Psalm 18:29", d:"With God you can face things that would be impossible on your own. David was describing military realities but the principle is the same. There is a version of your life you can live in your own strength and there is a version available to you when you stop running on your own power and start drawing on his. The difference between those two versions is not your effort — it is your dependence. What is the wall in front of you right now?. — he can help you scale it." },
    { v:"The Lord will fight for you; you need only to be still.", r:"Exodus 14:14", d:"The Lord will fight for you — you need only to be still. Israel was standing between the Egyptian army and the Red Sea — there was no human solution — the instruction was not to figure something out. It was to stop striving, stop panicking, and watch what God was about to do. Some situations are not yours to solve. They are his to handle while you hold your position and keep your eyes on him — be still. Let him fight this one." },
    { v:"For at that time I will change the speech of the peoples to a pure speech, that all of them may call upon the name of the Lord and serve him with one accord.", r:"Zephaniah 3:9", d:"God promised a day when all the divisions that separate people would be healed, when pure speech would unite what confusion had scattered, and all people would call on his name together. You live in a world full of noise and division. But you belong to a kingdom where the final word is unity in him. Let that shape how you speak, how you treat people, how you build bridges instead of walls — you are a citizen of the coming kingdom — live like it now." },
    { v:"Everyone who believes that Jesus is the Christ has been born of God, and everyone who loves the Father loves whoever has been born of him.", r:"1 John 5:1", d:"Believing that Jesus is the Christ is not just an intellectual position — it is a relationship. And from that relationship flows love for the one who called you and love for everyone else he has called. Your faith and your love are not separate departments of your life — they are connected. The depth of your love for God will show up in the quality of how you love people. And the way you love people reveals something true about how much you actually believe what you say you believe." },
    { v:"Beloved, let us love one another, for love is from God, and whoever loves has been born of God and knows God.", r:"1 John 4:7", d:"Love is not native to human beings — it comes from God. Which means every time you genuinely love someone, you are carrying something of God into that person's life. The love that forgives when it would be easier to hold a grudge. The love that shows up when it would be easier to stay home. The love that speaks truth when it would be easier to stay quiet — that kind of love does not originate with you. It flows through you from the one who is love." },
    { v:"I go before you and will level the mountains; I will break down gates of bronze and cut through bars of iron.", r:"Isaiah 45:2", d:"God goes before you — that is not a metaphor. It means the territory you are walking into has already been visited by the one who is sending you. The obstacles, the opposition, the things that look like they will stop you, he has already been there — he levels the rough places before you arrive — you are not pioneering into unknown territory alone. You are following behind the God who has already cleared the path. What looks impassable to you is not impassable to him." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous, for you are the one who will lead these people.", r:"Joshua 1:6", d:"Be strong and courageous because of what God is doing through you, not just for you. Joshua's strength was called for because other people were depending on his leadership. Your faithfulness, your courage, your willingness to step into what God is asking, rarely affects only you. Someone in your life is waiting to see you step forward. Someone needs to watch you be brave. The strength God is building in you is not just for your benefit — it is for theirs." },
    { v:"I have fought the good fight, I have finished the race, and I have remained faithful.", r:"2 Timothy 4:7", d:"At the end of his life, in prison, facing execution, Paul's evaluation of himself was not a list of accomplishments — it was three statements about faithfulness — i fought — i finished — i kept the faith. Not I achieved everything I set out to — not I never failed — he fought the fight he was given — he ran the race set before him — he held onto his faith through everything — that is the goal — not perfection — faithfulness to the end." },
    { v:"And now the prize awaits me — the crown of righteousness, which the Lord, the righteous Judge, will give me.", r:"2 Timothy 4:8", d:"The crown is not for the most gifted or the most visible or the most successful. It is for those who have loved his appearing, who have stayed faithful across time, who have kept their eyes on the finish line when it would have been easier to look somewhere else. The judge who awards it is righteous — that means the verdict will be accurate. You cannot earn what you do not deserve and you cannot lose what has been stored up for your faithfulness — keep going." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Paul disciplined his body not because the body is bad but because the body is consequential — what you do with it matters. The consistency you build in your physical life, the habits you establish, the choices you make when no one is watching, these things are connected to the credibility and integrity of everything else you do and say — you cannot compartmentalize. Who you are in the small disciplines is who you are — train accordingly." },
    { v:"So I run with purpose in every step. I am not just shadowboxing.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:26", d:"There is a difference between being active and being purposeful — you can be busy going nowhere — you can put in effort that produces nothing. Paul ran with purpose in every step — he trained with a target in mind. The question is not just whether you are working hard. It is whether what you are working hard toward is the right thing — define your target — then run toward it with everything you have." },
    { v:"Be still before the Lord and wait patiently for him; fret not yourself over the one who prospers in his way, over the man who carries out evil devices.", r:"Psalm 37:7", d:"Be still and wait. Stop looking sideways at the people who seem to be getting further ahead while doing it wrong. The prosperity of the wicked is temporary, and spending your energy being frustrated by it is a waste of what God wants to do in you — focus on your lane — keep walking in faithfulness. God's justice is thorough and his timing is his own. You do not have to manage what belongs to him. Stay still and trust the one who sees everything." },
    { v:"What shall we say? If God is for us, who can ever be against us?", r:"Romans 8:31", d:"If God is for you, the question of who can stand against you has only one answer — nobody. That does not mean opposition will not come — it means opposition does not win. No person, no circumstance, no accumulated failure, no voice from your past can overpower the fact that the God of everything is on your side. The weight of that truth should change how you walk into every situation today — you do not walk in alone — you walk in with God." },
    { v:"In the shelter of your presence you hide them from the plots of men; you store them in your shelter from the strife of tongues.", r:"Psalm 31:20", d:"God hides you in his presence — that is not isolation — it is protection at the most intimate level. The plots of people who want to work against you, the coordinated criticism, the character attacks, the schemes that would undermine what God is building in your life, none of them have access to the place where he keeps you. You are held in a shelter that human schemes cannot reach — rest in that today." },
    { v:"You are a hiding place for me; you preserve me from trouble; you surround me with shouts of deliverance.", r:"Psalm 32:7", d:"God surrounds you with songs of deliverance — not just rescues you quietly — he celebrates your deliverance with sound. The God who saves you also sings over the saving. Whatever trouble you are currently in, whatever you are asking him to bring you through, picture this: on the other side of it, he is already singing. The rescue is as certain as the celebration that follows it — he preserves those who trust him — that is who he is." },
  ],
  6: [
    { v:"Let us run with endurance the race God has set before us.", r:"Hebrews 12:1", d:"You are not running this race without an audience. The cloud of witnesses is every person who has run before you and finished. They are proof that it can be done — that the race is finishable — that endurance is possible — and because they finished, you can too. Lay down the weight that slows you down. Lay down the sin that keeps tripping you. Fix your eyes on the finish line and run — not just to participate — to finish." },
    { v:"We do this by keeping our eyes on Jesus, the champion who initiates and perfects our faith.", r:"Hebrews 12:2", d:"Jesus ran the race before you and he did not stop. He endured the cross because he could see the joy on the other side of it. He did not despise the shame because he knew what the shame was producing. That is the example you are fixing your eyes on — not someone who had it easy. Someone who had it harder than you ever will and kept going anyway. When you feel like stopping, look at him — he finished — so can you." },
    { v:"Think of all the hostility he endured from sinful people; then you won't become weary and give up.", r:"Hebrews 12:3", d:"Think about what Jesus endured — not in a vague, religious way. Actually think about it — the hostility — the rejection from the people he came to save — the betrayal by someone in his inner circle — the injustice of the trial — the physical suffering. He endured all of it and he did not quit. He is your template for not becoming weary or losing heart. Your difficulty is real — his was too — and he finished. Let that fund your endurance today." },
    { v:"Don't you realize that in a race everyone runs, but only one person gets the prize? So run to win!", r:"1 Corinthians 9:24", d:"Run to win — that is what Paul says — not run to finish — not run to participate — run to win. The Christian life is not meant to be lived at a comfortable, minimal effort pace. It is meant to be pursued with everything you have, with the intensity of someone who knows what the prize is and is willing to do what it takes to get it — the prize is worth the cost. Run like you believe that." },
    { v:"All athletes are disciplined in their training. They do it to win a prize that will fade away, but we do it for an eternal prize.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:25", d:"Athletes endure tremendous discipline for something that is temporary — a season of recognition — a trophy that sits on a shelf. If that level of discipline exists for something that fades, what kind of discipline is appropriate for something that never fades?. The imperishable prize God has set before you is worth more than anything any competition could offer — train accordingly. Give this the best of what you have." },
    { v:"Likewise the Spirit helps us in our weakness. For we do not know what to pray for as we ought, but the Spirit himself intercedes for us with groanings too deep for words.", r:"Romans 8:26", d:"There are moments when you do not know what to pray. The situation is too complicated or the pain is too raw or you have run out of words. God has provision for exactly those moments — the Spirit intercedes with groanings too deep for words — you do not have to get your prayer right. You do not have to have the theology sorted before you approach him. Bring your wordless need to God and let the Spirit carry it the rest of the way." },
    { v:"Consider it pure joy, my brothers and sisters, whenever you face trials of many kinds, because you know that the testing of your faith produces perseverance.", r:"James 1:2-3", d:"The trials that come your way are not interruptions to your growth — they are the method of it. When your faith is tested, something is being built in you that a comfortable life never could — it is not that you should enjoy suffering. It is that you should understand what it is producing — endurance — rootedness. The kind of character that holds under pressure because it was built under pressure. The testing is not the end — it is the beginning of something stronger." },
    { v:"More than that, we rejoice in our sufferings, knowing that suffering produces endurance, and endurance produces character, and character produces hope.", r:"Romans 5:3-4", d:"The chain runs one direction and it starts with suffering — suffering to endurance — endurance to character — character to hope. You cannot get to hope on this path without going through the other things first — that is not bad news — it is the map. If you are in the suffering right now, you are at the beginning of the chain, not at a dead end — keep walking the chain. Every step is producing something you cannot see yet but that is absolutely real." },
    { v:"Patient endurance is what you need now, so that you will continue to do God's will.", r:"Hebrews 10:36", d:"You do not need more information right now — you need endurance. The knowledge of what God has promised is already in you. What is required is the patient faithfulness to keep doing what is right until the promise arrives. God's timing is not your timing. His seasons do not always align with your expectation — but his word always delivers. Hold on to what he has promised — do not let go before the season turns." },
    { v:"So do not throw away this confident trust in the Lord. Remember the great reward it brings you!", r:"Hebrews 10:35", d:"Do not throw away your confidence — it has a great reward — the confidence Paul is talking about is not arrogance. It is the settled assurance that God means what he said — that he will do what he promised. That your faithfulness is not going unnoticed and will not go unrewarded — you built that confidence through hard things. Do not let a difficult season make you trade it in. Hold on to what God has proven to you — it is worth everything." },
    { v:"But as for you, be strong and do not give up, for your work will be rewarded.", r:"2 Chronicles 15:7", d:"Be strong and do not give up. God said this to people who were returning to him after a long season of walking away — not to people who had been perfect — to people who were coming back. And his word to them was not shame or condemnation. It was strength and the assurance that their work of returning would be rewarded. Whatever season of drifting you are returning from, God's word to you is the same — your work will be rewarded — do not give up now." },
    { v:"For God so loved the world, that he gave his only Son, that whoever believes in him should not perish but have eternal life.", r:"John 3:16", d:"God did not observe the world from a distance and decide it was worth saving — he loved it and then he moved. The love came first and the action followed directly from it — he gave his only Son. That is the shape of the love God has for you. Specific, costly, sacrificial, and absolutely certain — you are not someone God is tolerating. You are someone he moved heaven and earth to reach — that love is the foundation of everything. Let it be the thing you build your life on." },
    { v:"So then, as we have opportunity, let us do good to everyone, and especially to those who are of the household of faith.", r:"Galatians 6:10", d:"Do good to everyone — not just the people who do good to you. Not just the people in your immediate community — everyone — and especially the household of faith. The people you worship with, the ones you do life with in Christ, they deserve your particular attention and investment. Community does not build itself. It requires people who show up, who give, who serve, who remain even when it would be easier to leave — be that person." },
    { v:"I press on to reach the end of the race and receive the heavenly prize for which God is calling us.", r:"Philippians 3:14", d:"Press on — not drift toward — not casually move in the direction of — press — the language is intentional — there is resistance — there are things that pull against forward motion — comfort, complacency, discouragement, distraction. Pressing means moving against that resistance with your full intention and effort. The prize at the end of this race is worth the pressing. Keep your eyes on it. Keep moving toward it — do not let the resistance be the last word." },
    { v:"For the word of God is living and active, sharper than any two-edged sword, piercing to the division of soul and of spirit, of joints and of marrow, and discerning the thoughts and intentions of the heart.", r:"Hebrews 4:12", d:"The Word of God is not passive information. It is living and active, working in you at a level deeper than you can manage on your own — when you open it, something happens — not just to your understanding but to your heart. It reaches the things you have been protecting and keeping hidden, the divided loyalties, the unspoken intentions. Let it do that work — do not read Scripture to check a box. Read it to be reached by something more accurate than your own self-assessment." },
    { v:"Now faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen.", r:"Hebrews 11:1", d:"Faith is not wishful thinking. It is the substance of what is hoped for — actual substance — real weight. Faith is the evidence that the invisible things are real, not the evidence that you have managed to believe hard enough. What God has promised is already real whether you can see it yet or not — your faith does not make it real — it aligns you with what is already true. Stand on what God has said. It holds more weight than what your circumstances currently look like." },
    { v:"Do you not know that your body is a temple of the Holy Spirit within you, whom you have from God? You are not your own, for you were bought with a price. So glorify God in your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:19-20", d:"Your body is a temple. That is not a metaphor for taking care of your health, though it includes that — it is a declaration about where God lives — the Holy Spirit has taken up residence in you. That changes what your body is for and what you do with it. You were bought with a price that was paid in full on the cross. What you do with your body matters to the one who bought it. Honor him with how you treat what belongs to him." },
    { v:"Remember that the Lord will give you an inheritance as your reward, and that the Master you are serving is Christ.", r:"Colossians 3:24", d:"You are not working for the approval of people who may or may not notice. You are working for the Lord, and from the Lord you will receive the inheritance as your reward — that changes the entire calculation. When no one else sees what you are doing, when the work is invisible and unrecognized, when faithfulness is costing you more than you feel like it should, remember who the real employer is — he sees all of it — and he rewards what he sees." },
    { v:"But the one who endures to the end will be saved.", r:"Matthew 10:22", d:"The one who endures to the end will be saved — not the one who started well — not the one who showed the most potential — the one who endured. Faith is not a moment — it is a marathon. The Christian life calls for long obedience in the same direction. The world will not always be friendly to your faith. Some seasons will actively work against it — endure anyway. The finish line is real and so is the one waiting for you there." },
    { v:"Remain faithful even when facing death, and I will give you the crown of life.", r:"Revelation 2:10", d:"Be faithful even to the point of death. God said that to a church that was about to face actual persecution. The crown of life he promises is not for the people who had the easiest path. It is for the people who were found faithful at the hardest point. Whatever you are facing that is testing your faithfulness right now, this is God's word to you: hold on — stay true — the crown is being prepared — do not walk away before you receive it." },
    { v:"Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. Not as the world gives do I give to you. Let not your hearts be troubled, neither let them be afraid.", r:"John 14:27", d:"The peace Jesus leaves you is not the kind the world offers. The world's peace depends on things going well, on resolution, on the absence of threat. Jesus offers peace that operates while the threat is still present, while the situation is still unresolved, while the storm has not yet passed. He gives it to you not as a future promise but as a present possession. You have access to this peace right now in the middle of whatever is hard — take it." },
    { v:"In the same way, let your good deeds shine out for all to see, so that everyone will praise your heavenly Father.", r:"Matthew 5:16", d:"Your life is meant to point somewhere. The good you do, the way you love people, the integrity you carry, the grace you show in difficulty, all of it is a light that shines into people's lives and points them toward God — you are not doing good to be seen. You are doing it so that people see God through you. That is a different motivation entirely and it produces a different quality of light. Let your life be something that makes people look up." },
    { v:"We are pressed on every side by troubles, but we are not crushed. We get knocked down, but we are not destroyed.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:8–9", d:"You are pressed but not crushed — perplexed but not despairing — persecuted but not abandoned. Struck down but not destroyed — read that list again. Everything on the left side is real — the pressure, the confusion, the feeling of being hit. But none of it gets to the word after the but — that word is held in place by God himself. You can be honest about how hard this is and still refuse to let it have the final say — both are true at the same time." },
    { v:"Therefore do not be anxious about tomorrow, for tomorrow will be anxious for itself. Sufficient for the day is its own trouble.", r:"Matthew 6:34", d:"Today has enough in it to deal with without borrowing trouble from tomorrow. God has given you exactly what you need for this day. Not for next week, not for the crisis that might come in six months — for today. When anxiety tries to drag you into a future that has not happened yet, bring it back. God is Lord of tomorrow too. He will give you what you need for it when you get there. Right now, today is your assignment." },
    { v:"For our struggle is not against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the powers of this dark world.", r:"Ephesians 6:12", d:"The fight you are in is not primarily against the people who have hurt you or the circumstances that are working against you — the real opposition is spiritual — that does not make the visible things less real. But it means the weapons that work are not the ones you are most tempted to reach for. Anger, retaliation, striving in your own strength. Those do not work on the actual enemy. Prayer, truth, faith, righteousness — those do." },
    { v:"My soul is bereft of peace; I have forgotten what happiness is. So I say, My endurance has perished; so has my hope from the Lord.", r:"Lamentations 3:17-18", d:"I have forgotten what happiness is — so I say my hope has perished. Jeremiah does not dress up the worst moments — he names them — there are seasons where honest faith sounds like that. Where the hope feels gone and you have to say so out loud before you can find your way back to it — do not pretend. Bring the honest grief to God — he can handle it. The path back to hope usually starts with telling the truth about where you actually are." },
    { v:"I have learned, in whatever situation I am, to be content.", r:"Philippians 4:11", d:"Contentment is not a gift — it is a lesson. Paul learned it through the full range of circumstances: abundance and scarcity, recognition and obscurity, freedom and imprisonment — you cannot learn contentment from a book. You learn it by going through things that would be easier to be discontent about and choosing differently — the contentment God offers is not resignation. It is the deep peace of someone who has settled the question of where their stability comes from." },
    { v:"Even when I walk through the darkest valley, I will not be afraid, for you are close beside me.", r:"Psalm 23:4", d:"Even in the darkest valley, you are not alone. The presence of God does not remove the valley — it accompanies you through it. His rod and his staff are tools of an active shepherd, not decorations. He is protecting you, guiding you, keeping you from falling off the edges — the darkness is real — so is the one walking through it with you — you will come out the other side — he has never lost anyone in the valley." },
    { v:"Seek the Lord while he may be found; call upon him while he is near.", r:"Isaiah 55:6", d:"Seek the Lord while he may be found — there is an urgency to that invitation. Not because God is unpredictable or might become unavailable but because the moments of spiritual openness in your own life have their own seasons. There are times when your heart is particularly ready to receive, when the Spirit is particularly at work, when the distance between you and God is particularly small — this is one of those times — do not let it pass — seek him now." },
    { v:"Now may the God of peace who brought again from the dead our Lord Jesus, the great shepherd of the sheep, by the blood of the eternal covenant, equip you with everything good that you may do his will.", r:"Hebrews 13:20-21", d:"The God of peace equips you with everything you need to do his will — everything — nothing is missing. He does not send you into what he has called you to without giving you what you need to do it. The equipping comes from the same God who raised Jesus from the dead. The power behind your calling is the power of resurrection. Whatever he is asking of you today, he has already provided what it takes — walk in that confidence." },
  ],
  7: [
    { v:"So if the Son sets you free, you are truly free.", r:"John 8:36", d:"The freedom Christ gives is not theoretical — it is actual liberation from what was holding you — the habits that had power over you — the shame that kept you small. The fear that kept you from being who God made you to be. If the Son sets you free, you are free indeed — not partially free. Not free in some areas but not others — free. You do not have to keep living as if you are still captive to what Christ has already released you from." },
    { v:"You have been called to live in freedom. Use your freedom to serve one another in love.", r:"Galatians 5:13", d:"You have been called to freedom. But freedom in Christ is not the freedom to do whatever you want. It is the freedom to love people without the weight of self-interest distorting everything. Freedom in the kingdom looks like service, like giving yourself away for others, like using your liberty to build someone else up rather than to indulge yourself. That is the shape of the freedom Christ purchased — use it well." },
    { v:"And you will know the truth, and the truth will set you free.", r:"John 8:32", d:"The truth that sets you free is not information — it is encounter. It is the deep, personal knowledge of who God actually is that comes from walking with him over time. The lies you have believed about yourself, about what you deserve, about what is possible for you, cannot survive sustained contact with what is actually true. Pursue the truth about God. Let it do its work. Freedom follows from knowing, not just from being told." },
    { v:"Wherever the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:17", d:"Where the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom. That means the presence of God in your life is itself a liberating force. You do not have to manage your way to freedom or discipline yourself out of bondage — the Spirit does what willpower cannot. His presence in you is actively producing the freedom that Christ paid for. Invite him into the places that still feel bound. He does not require you to fix yourself before he comes in — he comes in and then the fixing happens." },
    { v:"Many are the plans in a person's heart, but it is the Lord's purpose that prevails.", r:"Proverbs 19:21", d:"You can plan as carefully as you want and God's purposes will still prevail — that is not a threat — it is a relief — you are not responsible for making everything work out. You are responsible for faithfulness in what is in front of you. God is responsible for the outcome. Make your plans with wisdom and effort, then hold them loosely. When his purposes redirect what you planned, trust that where he is taking you is better than where you were heading." },
    { v:"You will seek me and find me, when you seek me with all your heart.", r:"Jeremiah 29:13", d:"You will find God when you seek him with your whole heart — not when your life is in order — not after you have cleaned yourself up — when you seek him with everything you have — the seeking itself is the access — you do not have to qualify to approach him. You just have to come with your whole heart, honestly, without holding anything back. He meets that kind of seeking every single time — he promised it — he keeps his word." },
    { v:"For the gifts and the calling of God are irrevocable.", r:"Romans 11:29", d:"The gifts and calling God placed on your life are not revocable. He does not give them to you and then take them back when you fail or drift or go through a season of spiritual wilderness. The calling was placed before you earned it and it holds through the seasons when you cannot feel it — you have not lost your purpose — you have not been disqualified. The gifts are still there — so is the calling — come back to them." },
    { v:"For by grace you have been saved through faith. And this is not your own doing; it is the gift of God, not a result of works, so that no one may boast.", r:"Ephesians 2:8-9", d:"You did not earn your way in. You were given access by grace through faith, and even the faith was not your own achievement. This matters not just for your theology but for the way you live. You cannot earn more of God's love by doing better — you cannot lose it by failing. The foundation is not your performance — it is his grace — stand on that. Stop trying to earn what was always a gift." },
    { v:"Who shall separate us from the love of Christ? Shall tribulation, or distress, or persecution, or famine, or nakedness, or danger, or sword?", r:"Romans 8:35", d:"What could separate you from the love of Christ?. Paul lists seven real possibilities: trouble, hardship, persecution, famine, nakedness, danger, sword — he had personally experienced most of them. And his conclusion was the same every time he ran through the list — nothing. None of those things, severe as they are, have the power to cut you off from the love of Christ. You can go through the worst and come out still held. His love does not break under pressure." },
    { v:"Since he did not spare even his own Son but gave him up for us all, won't he also give us everything else?", r:"Romans 8:32", d:"God did not spare his own Son — he gave him for you. If he was willing to do that, the most costly thing imaginable, there is nothing lesser that he is withholding from you out of indifference. The cross is the proof of his willingness to give. He is not a God who holds back from his children — he is a God who gave everything. Trust him with what you need. He has already demonstrated that he is willing to provide it." },
    { v:"I am the vine; you are the branches. Those who remain in me, and I in them, will produce much fruit.", r:"John 15:5", d:"Apart from Christ you can do nothing — that is not a discouraging statement — it is a clarifying one. It tells you exactly where the source of all real fruit is — you are not the vine — you are the branch — your job is not to produce. Your job is to stay connected to the one who produces through you — when you abide in him, fruit happens. When you disconnect and try to generate it on your own, you get busy but not fruitful — stay connected. Let him do the producing." },
    { v:"But if you remain in me and my words remain in you, you may ask for anything you want, and it will be granted!", r:"John 15:7", d:"If you remain in Christ and his words remain in you, ask whatever you wish and it will be given to you — the condition is not about earning the right answer. It is about being so aligned with God, so shaped by his word, so rooted in his presence, that what you ask has already been formed by him. When you are truly abiding, the desires of your heart start to match his. The asking becomes an expression of the abiding rather than a request to a distant God." },
    { v:"What does the Lord require of you? To act justly and to love mercy and to walk humbly with your God.", r:"Micah 6:8", d:"Act justly — love mercy. Walk humbly with your God — three things — not a long list of religious requirements — three. God is not asking for elaborate religious performance. He is asking for the quality of your character in how you treat people, the posture of your heart toward grace, and the orientation of your daily life toward him. These three things, practiced consistently over a lifetime, are what faithfulness actually looks like." },
    { v:"Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.", r:"Matthew 22:37", d:"Love the Lord your God with all your heart, soul, and mind — not the parts of you that feel spiritual. Not the parts you have already given over to him — all — every faculty — every thought — every desire. He is not asking for a portion of your devotion — he is asking for everything. Not because he is demanding but because a divided love produces a divided life. When he has all of you, everything else falls into its right place." },
    { v:"Love your neighbor as yourself.", r:"Matthew 22:39", d:"Love your neighbor as yourself. The standard is not how well you treat strangers or how consistent your charitable giving is. It is how well you love yourself and then offering that same quality of care to the people around you. The health of your love for others is connected to the health of how you regard yourself — you cannot pour from empty. Take care of yourself so you have something to give to the people God has placed in your life." },
    { v:"Abide in me, and I in you. As the branch cannot bear fruit by itself, unless it abides in the vine, neither can you, unless you abide in me.", r:"John 15:4", d:"A branch that has been separated from the vine does not produce less fruit — it produces none — there is no partial connection that produces partial results — the connection is everything. When you feel dry, when nothing is growing, when the life feels absent, the question is not what you need to do more of — it is whether you are actually abiding — return to him — stay there — the fruit follows the connection, not the effort." },
    { v:"God will generously provide all you need. Then you will always have everything you need and plenty left over to share with others.", r:"2 Corinthians 9:8", d:"God is able to make all grace abound to you — not some grace — not enough to get by — all grace. So that at all times, in all things, you have all you need. His provision is not rationed to the minimum. It is poured out in abundance, with enough left over for every good work he has prepared for you to do. You do not have to hoard what God has given you — he does not run out. Give generously from the overflow he has placed in your hands." },
    { v:"For I know the one in whom I trust, and I am sure that he is able to guard what I have entrusted to him.", r:"2 Timothy 1:12", d:"I know who I have believed in — that is where Paul's confidence came from — not in his own track record — not in his theological precision — in the person of God himself. When you know who God is, when you have spent enough time in his presence to know him personally and not just about him, trust comes naturally. Because trust follows from knowledge of the one being trusted. Spend time knowing him — the confidence will follow." },
    { v:"The Lord himself goes before you and will be with you; he will never leave you nor forsake you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:8", d:"God goes before you — he is with you — he will never leave you or forsake you. Three promises stacked together for a reason — the courage they produce is not generated from within. It is drawn from the reality that you are not navigating your life alone — he is ahead, clearing the way — he is beside you, walking through it. He is behind you, ensuring nothing follows that he has not already addressed — you are completely covered — do not be afraid." },
    { v:"Glory to God in highest heaven, and peace on earth to those with whom God is pleased.", r:"Luke 2:14", d:"Glory to God in the highest and peace on earth to those with whom he is pleased. The angels announced this at the birth of Jesus in an occupied land, to shepherds who were among the lowest in their society. God's peace arrived not in palaces but in a stable — not to the powerful but to the ordinary. His coming was not what anyone expected. His presence still shows up in the unexpected places. Keep your eyes open for it." },
    { v:"When you did it to one of the least of these my brothers and sisters, you were doing it to me.", r:"Matthew 25:40", d:"When you served the hungry, the sick, the stranger, the imprisoned, you served Christ — that is the connection Jesus makes — not a metaphor — not an analogy. He says when you did it to the least of these you did it to me. The person in front of you who needs something carries the face of Jesus in a way that is more than poetic. How you treat the overlooked people in your life is how you treat God. Let that change how you see everyone around you." },
    { v:"Live as people who are free, not using your freedom as a cover-up for evil, but living as servants of God.", r:"1 Peter 2:16", d:"You are free, not to do what you want, but to serve — that is the shape of freedom in the kingdom. The one who has been set free from sin and self is now free to pour themselves out for others without the depletion that comes from living for yourself. Freedom in Christ is not permission to live however you want. It is liberation into the kind of life that actually fulfills what you were made for. Use it to serve — that is what it is for." },
    { v:"You keep him in perfect peace whose mind is stayed on you, because he trusts in you.", r:"Isaiah 26:3", d:"Perfect peace is available to the mind that stays fixed on God — not the mind that has everything figured out. Not the mind that has no hard things to process. The mind that is anchored on him regardless of what is happening around it. You will not find that peace by managing your circumstances until they stop being difficult. You will find it by making God the settled, fixed reference point for everything else. Anchor your mind there — the peace follows." },
    { v:"Whatever you do or say, do it as a representative of the Lord Jesus, giving thanks through him to God the Father.", r:"Colossians 3:17", d:"Everything you do can be an act of worship. The work you do in this gym, the conversation you have on the way home, the way you treat the person you live with, how you do your job. All of it can be done in the name of the Lord Jesus, as a representative of him — that is not a heavy weight to carry — it is an invitation to make the ordinary sacred — do everything as an offering. Let your whole life be the worship." },
    { v:"For from him and through him and to him are all things. To him be glory forever. Amen.", r:"Romans 11:36", d:"From him and through him and to him are all things — everything originates in God. Everything is sustained by him. Everything is ultimately moving toward him — your life is not the exception to that. Your work, your relationships, your suffering, your joy, all of it is caught up in a story that begins and ends in God himself. When life feels chaotic or purposeless, come back to this — it is all held together in him — to him be the glory." },
    { v:"For I am not ashamed of the gospel, for it is the power of God for salvation to everyone who believes, to the Jew first and also to the Greek.", r:"Romans 1:16", d:"Paul was writing from a world where being identified with a crucified criminal was a social liability — and he said I am not ashamed. Not because the message had been accepted or because people were impressed — but because he knew what it was. The power of God for salvation — not a helpful philosophy — not a moral improvement system. The actual power of God working actual salvation for every person who believes — that is what you carry — be bold with it." },
    { v:"The Lord said to Abram, Go from your country and your kindred and your father's house to the land that I will show you.", r:"Genesis 12:1", d:"Go. God said that to Abram before he told him where he was going. Leave everything familiar and go to the land I will show you — not the land I will describe to you now — the land I will show you as you walk — the call of God often works this way — he gives you enough to take the first step — the rest of the direction comes as you move. Stop waiting until you can see the whole plan. Take the step he has already shown you." },
    { v:"Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you.", r:"Matthew 7:7", d:"Ask — seek — knock. Three commands, each one more active than the last. God is not rationing his access to people who have earned the right to approach him — he is inviting you to keep coming. To ask persistently, to seek with your whole effort, to knock with the expectation that the door will open — he is not reluctant to give — he is waiting for you to keep asking — do not stop before the door opens." },
    { v:"Jesus said to them, I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst.", r:"John 6:35", d:"I am the bread of life. Whoever comes to me will never go hungry. Jesus uses the most basic human need, food, to point to the deepest human need: himself. Every substitute you have tried to satisfy that hunger with has left you needing more — he is the only one who actually fills it. The hunger that drives your worst decisions, that gets you into the relationships and habits that do not serve you, is a hunger that only he can feed — come to him." },
    { v:"I have set the Lord always before me; because he is at my right hand, I shall not be shaken.", r:"Psalm 16:8", d:"I have set the Lord always before me — that is a deliberate choice, not a spontaneous feeling. David placed God in front of him, made him the fixed reference point for every decision, every thought, every moment of the day. Because he is at my right hand, I will not be shaken. The stability is not accidental — it flows from a practice. Set him before you today — deliberately. Then walk through the day with that as your anchor." },
    { v:"If you keep my commandments, you will abide in my love, just as I have kept my Father's commandments and abide in his Father's love.", r:"John 15:10", d:"Jesus stayed in the Father's love by keeping his commandments. Not as a transaction but as the natural expression of who he was. Obedience is not the price of the relationship — it is the evidence that the relationship is real. When you love someone deeply, you care about what they care about. You do what honors them not because you have to but because the love makes you want to. That is the kind of obedience that keeps you in his love." },
  ],
  8: [
    { v:"Don't you realize that your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit, who lives in you and was given to you by God? You do not belong to yourself.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:19", d:"You are a temple — not a building that resembles one — a temple — the actual dwelling place of the living God. The Holy Spirit is not visiting — he lives in you. That changes the purpose and value of your body from something you own and manage to something that belongs to God. The way you treat your body, what you put into it, how you maintain it, how much sleep you give it, is part of how you steward the place where God has chosen to live." },
    { v:"For God bought you with a high price. So you must honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:20", d:"You were bought at a price. That price was the death of the Son of God. That means your body does not belong to you alone — it belongs to the one who paid for it. Honor God with your body is not a call to perfection — it is a call to intentionality. To treat what belongs to him with the care and respect appropriate for something that precious. Your body is not just yours to use — it is his to be stewarded." },
    { v:"So whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do it all for the glory of God.", r:"1 Corinthians 10:31", d:"Whether you eat or drink or whatever you do, do it all for the glory of God — the mundane things are included — the meal, the workout, the commute, the conversation. All of it can be offered to God as an act of worship — the goal is not to make everything feel spiritual. It is to bring an awareness of God's presence into everything, so that the ordinary is transformed into something that honors him. Let today be worship from first to last." },
    { v:"Dear friend, I hope all is well with you and that you are as healthy in body as you are strong in spirit.", r:"3 John 1:2", d:"God cares about your physical health as much as he cares about your spiritual health. He does not want you thriving spiritually while neglecting the body he gave you — he prays for your wholeness — all of it. The work you are putting into your body right now, the discipline, the consistency, the rest, is connected to the flourishing God wants for you in every area. Take care of the whole person — he made you complete, not compartmentalized." },
    { v:"Physical training is good, but training for godliness is much better, promising benefits in this life and in the life to come.", r:"1 Timothy 4:8", d:"Physical training has value — god acknowledges that — but it has a ceiling that godliness does not. What you are building in your relationship with God holds a promise for both this life and the one to come. That does not make the physical training meaningless — it puts it in its right place. Train your body with diligence. Train your soul with even more — both matter — one matters more." },
    { v:"So let the Holy Spirit guide your lives. Then you won't be doing what your sinful nature craves.", r:"Galatians 5:16", d:"Walk by the Spirit and you will not carry out the desires of the flesh. The solution to the patterns you are trying to break is not white-knuckling your way through willpower. It is staying so connected to the Spirit that his desires become yours. The fight against what pulls you down is won at the level of connection, not at the level of effort — stay close to God — let the Spirit lead. The resistance to what is wrong follows from the relationship." },
    { v:"Give your bodies to God because of all he has done for you. Let them be a living and holy sacrifice — the kind he will find acceptable.", r:"Romans 12:1", d:"Offer your body to God as a living sacrifice — this is your spiritual act of worship. The gym, the discipline, the early mornings, the sacrifice of comfort for consistency. When you do it as an offering to God and not just for yourself, it becomes something more than exercise — it becomes an act of worship. What you are doing with your body right now can be holy — offer it to him. Let it count for something beyond the physical." },
    { v:"Whatever you do, work heartily, as for the Lord and not for men, knowing that from the Lord you will receive the inheritance as your reward.", r:"Colossians 3:23-24", d:"Work as if God is watching because he is. Not to perform for him but because his observation changes the quality of everything. When the audience is God, you cannot cut corners, cannot phone it in, cannot do just enough to get by. He sees the full effort and the half effort equally clearly — work from that awareness. Not in fear but in the freedom of knowing that what you do for him never goes unnoticed." },
    { v:"The human body has many parts, but the many parts make up one whole body.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:12", d:"The body of Christ works because every part is different and every part is needed. Your gifts, your perspective, your particular story and struggle and strength, the church needs them — you are not redundant — you are not there to fill a seat. You are a part of a whole that does not function correctly without what only you bring — show up — contribute — you are needed more than you know." },
    { v:"God has put each part just where he wants it.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:18", d:"God put each part of the body exactly where he wanted it — not approximately, not as a general guideline — exactly. That means your place in your community, your family, your church, your workplace is not accidental — he placed you there. The particular gifts you have and the particular needs around you were matched by design. Stop questioning why you are where you are and start asking what God wants to do through you in the place he has planted you." },
    { v:"Some parts of the body that seem weakest and least important are actually the most necessary.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:22", d:"The parts that seem weakest are actually indispensable. That runs against everything the world teaches about value and contribution — but God's economy works differently. The person who serves quietly, who prays consistently, who encourages without recognition, who does the work no one else wants to do, that person is essential — do not measure your contribution by visibility — measure it by faithfulness. The indispensable parts are often the ones no one can see." },
    { v:"All of you together are Christ's body, and each of you is a part of it.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:27", d:"You are part of the body of Christ. You are not a spectator to what God is doing — you are a participant. A member of the actual body through which Christ continues his work in the world. That makes everything you do as a follower of Christ significant — the way you love your family — the way you serve in your community. The way you show up for people in hard seasons. You are the hands and feet of Christ — take that seriously." },
    { v:"Your eyes saw my unformed substance; in your book were written, every one of them, the days that were formed for me, when as yet there was none of them.", r:"Psalm 139:16", d:"Before you were born, God had already written all the days of your life. That does not mean life is predetermined in a way that removes your choices. It means that the God who holds time wrote your name into his story before you could do anything to earn or lose your place in it. He saw you in the womb and he sees you now. Every day of your life was already in his book. You are not a surprise to him — you are known." },
    { v:"She is energetic and strong, a hard worker.", r:"Proverbs 31:17", d:"She is energetic and strong, a hard worker. The woman described in Proverbs 31 does not stumble into strength — she pursues it — she makes her arms strong. The physical capacity she carries is part of the character she has built. Strength is not vanity when it is rooted in purpose. The work you are doing to build your body is part of the full picture of who God is making you — work with intention — strength matters." },
    { v:"She watches over the affairs of her household and does not eat the bread of idleness.", r:"Proverbs 31:27", d:"She watches over the affairs of her household and does not eat the bread of idleness. Attention and diligence are the marks of this woman. Not perfection, not having it all together, but the consistent application of effort to the things that matter — idleness is not rest. It is the consumption of time without purpose — rest intentionally. But when it is time to work, work with the kind of attentiveness that honors what has been entrusted to you." },
    { v:"Lazy people want much but get little, but those who work hard will prosper.", r:"Proverbs 13:4", d:"The soul of the sluggard craves and gets nothing — the craving is real. The problem is not desire, it is the disconnect between wanting and doing. Desire without action is frustration. What you are putting effort into today is the thing that will bear fruit tomorrow. The soul of the diligent is richly supplied not because they wanted more but because they moved when the craving hit instead of sitting in it." },
    { v:"Work brings profit, but mere talk leads to poverty!", r:"Proverbs 14:23", d:"Work brings profit. Talk leads to poverty — that is a direct equation. There is a version of your life that looks productive because you talk about what you are going to do, plan what you intend to accomplish, discuss your goals at length. And there is a version where you do the work and let the results speak. The gap between those two versions is not talent or opportunity — it is action — do the work — stop talking about it." },
    { v:"Do nothing from selfish ambition or conceit, but in humility count others more significant than yourselves.", r:"Philippians 2:3", d:"Do nothing from selfish ambition or conceit, but in humility count others more significant than yourselves. That is not a call to think less of yourself. It is a call to think of others as fully as you think of yourself. To carry their interests with the same weight you carry your own — that posture transforms every interaction. When you walk into a room already asking what people need rather than what you can get, everything changes." },
    { v:"A peaceful heart leads to a healthy body; jealousy is like cancer in the bones.", r:"Proverbs 14:30", d:"A peaceful heart gives life to the body. What is happening on the inside is showing up on the outside whether you want it to or not. The stress you are carrying, the resentments you are holding onto, the anxiety you are running on, it is costing your body something — not just emotionally but physically. Peace is not just a spiritual virtue — it is a health strategy. Pursue it like the physical good it actually is." },
    { v:"Kind words are like honey — sweet to the soul and healthy for the body.", r:"Proverbs 16:24", d:"Kind words are like honey. They are sweet to the soul and healthy for the body. What you speak over yourself and what others speak over you has physical consequences. The words that have been deposited in your heart, the ones you replay when things get hard, they are either healing you or wearing you down. Choose what you listen to — choose what you say. Words that are rooted in what God says about you are the ones worth keeping." },
    { v:"Don't be deceived: God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows.", r:"Galatians 6:7", d:"You will reap what you sow — that is not a threat. It is a law built into the fabric of how things work. Every habit is a seed. Every repeated choice is planting something. You are always in the process of creating a future harvest, for better or worse. The question is not whether the law applies to you — it does — the question is what you are planting. Because what you consistently sow is what will eventually and inevitably grow." },
    { v:"If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me.", r:"Matthew 16:24", d:"Take up your cross and follow me. The cross was not a religious symbol in that moment — it was the instrument of execution. Jesus was telling his disciples that following him would cost something real. Something that looks like death to the world. The comforts, the self-protection, the claim to your own story, set them down. The life you find on the other side of that kind of surrender is the only one actually worth living." },
    { v:"The Lord nurses them when they are sick and restores them to health.", r:"Psalm 41:3", d:"The Lord nurses and sustains the person on their sickbed. God's care is not only for the spiritually strong. It extends to physical weakness, to the days when your body is failing, to the seasons when health is fragile. He is present in those moments in a specific, attentive way. If you are in a season of physical struggle, you are not outside of his care — he is in the room — he is tending what needs tending." },
    { v:"He heals the brokenhearted and bandages their wounds.", r:"Psalm 147:3", d:"He heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds — not from a distance — not through a system — he does it himself — the binding of wounds requires proximity. God gets that close to the places that hurt. The heartbreak in your life right now, the loss that has not fully healed, the grief that resurfaces unexpectedly, he is not looking at it from a safe distance — he is close enough to bandage it — let him in." },
    { v:"Great peace have those who love your law; nothing can make them stumble.", r:"Psalm 119:165", d:"Great peace belongs to those who love God's law — not who follow it perfectly — not who have never broken it — who love it. Who value it, who return to it, who find their footing in it. When the Word of God is not just a rule book but a gift you have come to love, peace comes with it. The stumbling that would otherwise send you into shame and spinning does not have the same power over the person rooted in his truth." },
    { v:"And I will put a new spirit in you. I will take out your stony, stubborn heart and give you a tender, responsive heart.", r:"Ezekiel 36:26", d:"God promises to take your heart of stone and replace it with a heart of flesh — not to improve the stone heart — to replace it. The stubbornness, the hardness, the inability to feel what you should feel, the patterns of the old life, God does not ask you to fix those things. He offers to do what you cannot do for yourself. Give him access to the parts that have gone hard — he can work with stone. His specialty is making them flesh again." },
    { v:"Rejoice in the Lord always; again I will say, rejoice. Let your reasonableness be known to everyone.", r:"Philippians 4:4-5", d:"Rejoice in the Lord always — and let your gentleness be known to everyone. Those two things together tell a story. The person who is genuinely rooted in joy does not have to fight for their position or defend their honor or insist on what they deserve — the gentleness flows from the joy. When you are secure in God, you hold your own needs loosely enough to be gentle with others. Joy and gentleness are connected — pursue both." },
    { v:"For to set the mind on the flesh is death, but to set the mind on the Spirit is life and peace.", r:"Romans 8:6", d:"The mind set on the Spirit is life and peace — not eventually — not after enough discipline. The mind set on the Spirit produces life and peace as its natural output. The direction of your mind is the direction of your life. What you habitually think about, return to, and allow to occupy your attention is forming you — set your mind deliberately. The peace you want is downstream of a mind that has been anchored in the right place." },
    { v:"Do you not know that you are God's temple and that God's Spirit dwells in you?", r:"1 Corinthians 3:16", d:"You are God's temple — not a building that houses something. You are the actual dwelling place of the Spirit of God. That is a statement about what you are, not just what you should aspire to. The Spirit is not looking for an invitation — he has already moved in. The question is how much access you are giving him to the rooms you have been keeping closed — open the whole house. Let him fill every part." },
    { v:"If then you have been raised with Christ, seek the things that are above, where Christ is, seated at the right hand of God.", r:"Colossians 3:1", d:"You have been raised with Christ — that is past tense — it has already happened. And because it has happened, the direction of your life has changed. Set your mind on things above. Not as a religious obligation but as the natural orientation of someone who has been raised to a new life — you are not the same person you were — your citizenship has changed. Let the way you think reflect where you actually belong." },
    { v:"Flee from sexual immorality. Every other sin a person commits is outside the body, but the sexually immoral person sins against his own body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:18", d:"Flee — not resist slowly — not manage carefully — flee. There are some things you do not try to moderate or handle with careful willpower — you get out — the body is not irrelevant to your spiritual life. What you do with it has consequences that go deeper than the physical. God takes the body seriously — so should you. When something is working against the integrity of your body and your spirit, the instruction is simple: leave." },
  ],
  9: [
    { v:"Commit your way to the Lord; trust in him, and he will act.", r:"Psalm 37:5", d:"Commit your way to the Lord and he will act — that is the order — you commit — he acts. Not he might act if you commit well enough — he will act — the commitment is yours to make — the outcome is his to produce. Too often we try to manage the outcome because we are not sure we trust God with it — but the promise is clear. When you genuinely roll your way onto him, he moves. Trust him enough to actually let go of the result." },
    { v:"In this you rejoice, though now for a little while, if necessary, you have been grieved by various trials, so that the tested genuineness of your faith may be found to result in praise and glory and honor at the revelation of Jesus Christ.", r:"1 Peter 1:6-7", d:"Your faith is being tested so that it can be proved genuine. Gold goes through fire to show that it is gold. The testing is not destroying what is real — it is revealing it. What God is doing in the hard season is not diminishing your faith. He is proving it, clarifying it, making clear what is solid and what was just surface. On the other side of this, what remains will be worth more than anything that could not survive the fire." },
    { v:"For the Lord disciplines the one he loves, and chastises every son whom he receives.", r:"Hebrews 12:6", d:"The Lord disciplines the ones he loves. Every parent who cares about their child's future makes hard calls for the sake of their growth. God does the same. The seasons of correction, of consequence, of divine redirection are not evidence that God is disappointed in you or has given up on you. They are evidence that he loves you too much to leave you exactly as you are. The discipline is a form of attention — it means he is invested." },
    { v:"For the Lord corrects those he loves, just as a father corrects a child in whom he delights.", r:"Proverbs 3:12", d:"God corrects those he loves just as a father corrects a child he delights in — notice that — the correction comes with delight, not with contempt — he is not fixing you because you disgust him — he is shaping you because he delights in you. Every time God allows something that redirects your path or challenges your assumptions, it is the action of a Father who sees more than you can see and cares about where you end up." },
    { v:"Don't reject the Lord's discipline, and don't be upset when he corrects you.", r:"Proverbs 3:11", d:"Do not despise the Lord's discipline and do not resent his correction. The temptation in a hard season is to read it as abandonment or punishment. But correction is the action of someone who is paying attention. God is not looking the other way. He is actively engaged in your life, shaping it toward something you cannot yet fully see. Receive the hard things with humility — they are part of how he works." },
    { v:"Ponder the path of your feet; then all your ways will be sure.", r:"Proverbs 4:26", d:"Think carefully about where your feet are taking you. The paths you walk consistently become the roads that shape your life — this is not a warning about dramatic wrong turns. It is a call to daily, intentional examination of direction. The small choices that seem insignificant add up — where are you habitually heading?. Is it where you want to end up?. Adjust now while the correction is small." },
    { v:"The heart of man plans his way, but the Lord establishes his steps.", r:"Proverbs 16:9", d:"You plan your route but God determines your steps — that is not a reason to stop planning. It is a reason to hold your plans loosely and stay attentive to where God is actually leading. The best plans made with the wisest strategy are still subject to the purposes of God. When he redirects, it is not a failure of the plan — it is the superior plan revealing itself. Follow where he leads, even when it differs from where you were heading." },
    { v:"Don't get sidetracked; keep your feet from following evil.", r:"Proverbs 4:27", d:"Do not swerve to the right or to the left. The drifting that takes people far from where they intended to be does not usually happen all at once — it happens in small deviations that compound over time — stay on the path. Resist the small compromises that feel harmless in the moment but accumulate into something you did not choose. The discipline of staying straight is easier to maintain than the work of finding your way back after a long drift." },
    { v:"We capture their rebellious thoughts and teach them to obey Christ.", r:"2 Corinthians 10:5", d:"Every thought that positions itself against what God says is true needs to be taken captive — not entertained — not reasoned with — captured. The mental battle you are in is real and the terrain is your mind. What you allow to occupy your thoughts will eventually show up in your choices. You have the authority to reject thoughts that contradict God's word about who you are and what is possible for you — take them captive. Replace them with what is true." },
    { v:"Fix your thoughts on what is true, and honorable, and right, and pure, and lovely, and admirable.", r:"Philippians 4:8", d:"Fix your thoughts on what is true, honorable, right, pure, lovely, and admirable — this is not spiritual escapism — it is a deliberate management of your mental diet. What you consistently feed your mind shapes your outlook, your decisions, and your emotional state. You have more control over what you think about than you usually exercise. Today, when your mind goes to what is wrong, pull it back to what is true and good and worth thinking about." },
    { v:"Set your minds on things that are above, not on things that are on earth.", r:"Colossians 3:2", d:"Set your mind on things above. Not as a rejection of the physical world but as the anchor that keeps everything earthly in its proper perspective. When your mind is rooted in the eternal, the temporary things lose their grip — the opinion that was bothering you — the comparison that was stealing your peace — the fear about tomorrow. They all look different when you are looking from the vantage point of what is above and what is real." },
    { v:"Don't worry about anything; instead, pray about everything. Tell God what you need, and thank him for all he has done.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Do not be anxious about anything — instead, pray about everything. The translation of anxiety into prayer is not denial — it is redirection — you are not pretending the worry does not exist. You are taking it somewhere it can actually be held. God is not annoyed by your repeated requests. He is not growing impatient with the same prayer you have brought him a hundred times — bring it again. That is exactly what he is asking you to do." },
    { v:"Then you will experience God's peace, which exceeds anything we can understand.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"The peace that passes understanding will guard your heart and mind — it does not make sense logically — you should be anxious given your circumstances. But the peace is there anyway, standing guard, holding the line between you and the anxiety that wants to flood back in — that peace is not something you manufacture. It is something God gives when you bring your worries to him — ask for it — then let it guard what you cannot guard yourself." },
    { v:"The Lord of hosts is with us; the God of Jacob is our fortress.", r:"Psalm 46:7", d:"The Lord of hosts is with you — the Lord of armies. The God who commands more forces than you can see is the one who is with you right now. Whatever you are facing feels large. It is not larger than the one who commands the hosts of heaven — you are not outmatched — you are not outgunned. You have access to a strength and a presence that puts everything working against you into its proper and diminished perspective." },
    { v:"So humble yourselves before God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you.", r:"James 4:7", d:"Resist the devil and he will flee — that is a direct promise. He does not dig in when you resist — he leaves — the power of resistance is real. But it starts in the right order: first submit to God, then resist the enemy — the authority to resist comes from the submission. You cannot hold the enemy off in your own strength. But from a position of surrender to God, you have the authority to tell the enemy to go — use it." },
    { v:"Come close to God, and God will come close to you.", r:"James 4:8", d:"Draw near to God and he will draw near to you. The movement is yours to initiate and his to respond to — that is an extraordinary promise. Every step you take toward God is met by a corresponding movement of God toward you. You do not have to work your way to his presence — you just have to move in his direction. Whatever has kept you at a distance, start closing that gap today — he is already moving toward you." },
    { v:"Humble yourselves before the Lord, and he will lift you up in honor.", r:"James 4:10", d:"Humble yourself before the Lord and he will lift you up — the lifting is his work — the humbling is yours — you cannot produce your own exaltation. You cannot manufacture your own promotion or engineer your own breakthrough — but you can position yourself under God's hand. And when you do, at the right time, in his perfect timing, he lifts — trust the process — do the humbling. Let him do the lifting." },
    { v:"Stay alert! Watch out for your great enemy, the devil. He prowls around like a roaring lion, looking for someone to devour.", r:"1 Peter 5:8", d:"The enemy is real, active, and looking for a foothold — he is not a concept or a symbol. He is a real adversary who prowls looking for someone to devour. The warning to be sober and alert is not paranoia — it is wisdom. What he is looking for is a gap in your attention, an area of your life left unguarded, a wound that has not been brought to God — stay alert — stay covered — do not give him what he is looking for." },
    { v:"Stand firm against him, and be strong in your faith.", r:"1 Peter 5:9", d:"Stand firm against the enemy, strong in your faith, knowing that your brothers and sisters throughout the world are going through the same kind of suffering — you are not the only one fighting this — you are not uniquely targeted or unusually weak — the battle is shared. The faith that holds you is the same faith holding millions of other believers in hard places right now — you are not alone in this. Stand firm in what you know — the company of the faithful stands with you." },
    { v:"Cast your burden on the Lord, and he will sustain you; he will never permit the righteous to be moved.", r:"Psalm 55:22", d:"Cast your burden on the Lord and he will sustain you — cast — not set gently — throw it. The weight of what you are carrying was never designed to be held by you alone. When you stop trying to manage the unmanageable and start actually giving it to God, the sustaining begins. He has never dropped what he has been given — he will not start with you. Give him what you have been holding and let him hold it instead." },
    { v:"We should live in this evil world with wisdom, righteousness, and devotion to God.", r:"Titus 2:12", d:"The grace of God is teaching you to say no. No to ungodliness, no to worldly passions, yes to self-controlled and godly living. Grace is not just forgiveness — it is formation. The same grace that covers your failures is actively working in you to produce something different — you are not just forgiven. You are being transformed by the very grace that saved you. Cooperate with what it is teaching you." },
    { v:"Let everything you say be good and helpful, so that your words will be an encouragement to those who hear them.", r:"Ephesians 4:29", d:"Let only helpful words come out of your mouth. Words that build up rather than tear down. Words that give grace to the people who hear them. You have the power every day to deposit something into people's lives or to withdraw from them. The choice is made word by word, conversation by conversation — choose to build — choose to give grace. Someone in your life today needs to hear something that will lift them. Be the one who says it." },
    { v:"Get rid of all bitterness, rage, anger, harsh words, and slander.", r:"Ephesians 4:31", d:"Get rid of all bitterness, rage, anger, harsh words, and slander — not manage — not reduce — get rid of — remove it. These things are not just bad habits. They are corrosive forces that eat away at what God is building in you and through you. Holding onto bitterness is holding onto something that is actively destroying you. The release of it is not just for the person who hurt you — it is for you. Let it go and give God room to work." },
    { v:"Instead, be kind to each other, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, just as God through Christ has forgiven you.", r:"Ephesians 4:32", d:"Forgive each other just as God in Christ forgave you — that is the standard — not as much as they deserve. As much as God forgave you. Which is fully, completely, at great cost, while you were still in the wrong — that is the model. The forgiveness that changes you and changes your relationships is not a feeling you wait for. It is a decision you make and then keep making until it becomes the truth — forgive — it is what you were forgiven to do." },
    { v:"Imitate God, therefore, in everything you do, because you are his dear children.", r:"Ephesians 5:1", d:"Imitate God — the audacity of that command is easy to miss. You are told to copy the behavior and love of the God who made everything. Not to admire it from a distance or to approximate it on good days — to imitate it — you can only imitate someone you have studied — you have to know him to reflect him. The more time you spend in his presence, in his word, in prayer, the more naturally his character shows up in yours." },
    { v:"For once you were full of darkness, but now you have light from the Lord. So live as people of light!", r:"Ephesians 5:8", d:"You were darkness — now you are light in the Lord — the change is total. Walk as children of light — not children trying to be light — children of it — what you carry has changed — where you came from has changed. You no longer belong to the darkness you used to live in. The way you live should reflect what you have become. Let the light in you be visible. Someone nearby is living in the dark and they need to see it." },
    { v:"Let love be genuine. Abhor what is evil; hold fast to what is good.", r:"Romans 12:9", d:"Let love be genuine — not performed — not strategic — not the kind that keeps score. Genuinely given without the calculation of what you will get back. Abhor what is evil and hold fast to what is good. The genuineness of the love is proven by what you hate and what you hold onto. Real love cannot coexist with what destroys people. If you love genuinely, you will fight for what is good and against what is evil. Let that shape how you show up today." },
    { v:"Because he holds fast to me in love, I will deliver him; I will protect him, because he knows my name.", r:"Psalm 91:14", d:"Because he holds fast to me in love, I will deliver him. The protection comes from the holding — from the clinging. From the refusal to let go even when everything around you suggests it would be easier to. God responds to the one who loves him and knows his name. Not the one who has the most theological knowledge or the most impressive spiritual resume — the one who holds fast — be that person." },
    { v:"Teach the older men to exercise self-control, to be worthy of respect, and to live wisely.", r:"Titus 2:2", d:"The qualities God calls for in a mature life are not gifts that appear suddenly. They are built over decades of small choices, of showing up faithfully when no one is watching, of practicing the character you want to have long before it feels natural — sober-minded — dignified — self-controlled. Sound in faith and love and steadfastness. These are not descriptions of a perfect person. They are the portrait of someone who has been faithful for a long time. That person is being built in you right now, one day at a time." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord with all your heart, and do not lean on your own understanding.", r:"Proverbs 3:5", d:"Trust the Lord with everything, not just the parts that feel manageable. The areas where you are holding the tightest are usually the ones that need his hand the most — your own understanding is limited — it can only process what is currently visible. God sees what you cannot. When you lean on your own understanding exclusively, you make decisions with partial information. When you trust him, you have access to the full picture. Let him see what you cannot." },
  ],
  10: [
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord, for he is good! His faithful love endures forever.", r:"Psalm 107:1", d:"Give thanks to the Lord for he is good — start there — not with your request list. Not with your complaints about what has not happened yet — with thankfulness rooted in who he is. His goodness does not rise and fall with your circumstances. His steadfast love endures forever. That word forever means it has not changed and it will not change. His goodness today is exactly what it has always been. That is worth naming out loud before you move on to anything else." },
    { v:"Always be joyful. Never stop praying. Be thankful in all circumstances.", r:"1 Thessalonians 5:16–18", d:"Rejoice always — pray without ceasing. Give thanks in all circumstances. Three commands that build on each other — the rejoicing is the posture — the praying is the practice — the thankfulness is the overflow. None of them require your circumstances to cooperate — all of them are rooted in who God is. This is the will of God for you, not someday when things are better — right now — in this season — today — start here." },
    { v:"Give thanks for everything to God the Father in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"Ephesians 5:20", d:"Give thanks for everything — that word everything is not an exaggeration — the hard things included — the unanswered prayers included — the seasons you would not have chosen included. Not because all things are good but because God is at work in all things and his purposes are good. Gratitude that includes the hard things is not naive — it is the deepest form of trust. It says I believe you are working even here — even in this." },
    { v:"Enter his gates with thanksgiving; go into his courts with praise. Give thanks to him and praise his name.", r:"Psalm 100:4", d:"Enter his presence with thanksgiving. Not arrive at thanksgiving eventually after you have spent enough time with him — come in already thankful. The posture with which you approach God shapes the quality of what you receive. Come in with a grateful heart and you will find him already there, ready to be praised, ready to speak, ready to work. Thankfulness is not the reward of a good time with God. It is the door you walk through to get there." },
    { v:"For the Lord is good. His unfailing love continues forever, and his faithfulness continues to each generation.", r:"Psalm 100:5", d:"The Lord is good — his love endures forever. His faithfulness continues to every generation. These are not things that have ever once been untrue. They did not stop being true during the hardest parts of your life. They did not take a break while you were going through the worst season. The faithfulness of God is not a fair weather characteristic — it runs through everything, without exception — that is the God you belong to — let it sink in." },
    { v:"I will praise you, Lord, with all my heart; I will tell of all the marvelous things you have done.", r:"Psalm 9:1", d:"I will praise you, Lord, with all my heart. I will tell of all the marvelous things you have done — praise is not passive. It is an act of will and it requires your whole heart. It also has a content: the things God has done — marvelous things. When was the last time you told someone what God has done in your life?. When was the last time you recounted it even to yourself?. Praise is the practice of remembering and declaring — do it today." },
    { v:"Let all that I am praise the Lord; with my whole heart, I will praise his holy name.", r:"Psalm 103:1", d:"Let all that I am praise the Lord — not just the spiritual part — not just the Sunday morning part — all of you. Your strength, your mind, your body, your effort, your gifts, your time. Everything can be oriented toward praise. Everything can be offered to him. Praise is not a compartment of your life — it is the orientation of the whole thing. Let all that you are, everything you have brought to this day, be offered to the one who gave it." },
    { v:"Let all that I am praise the Lord; may I never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Do not forget what God has done for you. This is a command because forgetting is easy, especially in the hard seasons. When the present difficulty is loud, the past faithfulness gets quiet. Make the habit of remembering deliberate — what has God done that you should not forget?. — what has he carried you through?. What has he provided that you did not provide for yourself?. — name it — out loud. Do not let the noise of today drown out the testimony of what he has already done." },
    { v:"He forgives all my sins and heals all my diseases.", r:"Psalm 103:3", d:"He forgives all your sins — he heals all your diseases — both — together. God is not just interested in the spiritual dimension of your life — he tends to the whole person. The forgiveness and the healing are listed in the same breath because they come from the same source. He is not a God who addresses one and ignores the other. Bring him your whole need, not just the parts that feel appropriately spiritual — he cares about all of it." },
    { v:"He fills my life with good things. My youth is renewed like the eagle's!", r:"Psalm 103:5", d:"He fills your life with good things — your youth is renewed like the eagle's. God is not a God of bare minimum provision — he fills — he renews — he restores what was depleted. The energy you feel like you have lost, the sense of purpose that has faded, the joy that has gone quiet, these are things he renews — not just spiritually but in your whole life. Let him fill what has gone empty. His provision is not rationed." },
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord and proclaim his greatness. Let the whole world know what he has done.", r:"Psalm 105:1", d:"Give thanks to the Lord and proclaim his greatness. Let the whole world know what he has done — your story is not just for you. What God has walked you through, the hard things he has carried you out of, the faithfulness he has shown in the seasons that nearly broke you, that testimony belongs to the people around you who need to hear it — do not keep it quiet. Someone needs to know what your God has done." },
    { v:"I will sing to the Lord because he is good to me.", r:"Psalm 13:6", d:"I will sing to the Lord because he has been good to me. This comes at the end of a psalm that opens with how long, Lord, will you forget me forever?. The movement from that desperation to singing is not because circumstances changed. It is because the Psalmist chose to locate one true thing and stand on it. God has been good to me — he has. Find that thing today and sing from it, even if it is the only thing you can find." },
    { v:"For he will hide me in his shelter in the day of trouble; he will conceal me under the cover of his tent; he will lift me high upon a rock.", r:"Psalm 27:5", d:"In the day of trouble, God hides you in his shelter. Conceals you under the cover of his tent. Lifts you high on a rock — the protection in this verse is comprehensive. Hidden from what is threatening, sheltered from the storm, elevated above the chaos. On the day when trouble is at its worst, you are not exposed — you are hidden in the safest possible place. Stay close to him — that is where the shelter is." },
    { v:"I will bless the Lord who guides me; even at night my heart instructs me.", r:"Psalm 16:7", d:"I will bless the Lord who guides me — even at night my heart instructs me. God does not stop communicating when the day gets quiet. The night hours when you cannot sleep, when the thoughts you have been outrunning all day finally catch you, those can be the times when God speaks most clearly — do not dread the quiet — pay attention in it. He is guiding you even then, even there, even in what feels like darkness." },
    { v:"For the Lord gives wisdom; from his mouth come knowledge and understanding.", r:"Proverbs 2:6", d:"The Lord gives wisdom. From his mouth come knowledge and understanding. Wisdom is not just intelligence or the accumulation of experience. It is a gift that flows from a relationship with the one who is wisdom itself. You can read every self-help book ever written and still lack what only he can give — ask him — he gives generously. The understanding you need for the decision in front of you today is available — go to the source." },
    { v:"No wonder my heart is glad, and I rejoice. My body rests in safety.", r:"Psalm 16:9", d:"My heart is glad — my soul rejoices. My body rests in safety — all three. The joy that comes from knowing God does not stay in the spiritual realm — it reaches your body — it affects your rest. It settles into your physical state in a way that improves how you function. Spiritual health and physical health are not separate. The gladness in your heart shows up in your face, your posture, your rest, your energy. Let God's joy reach all the way down." },
    { v:"You will show me the way of life, granting me the joy of your presence and the pleasures of living with you forever.", r:"Psalm 16:11", d:"In your presence there is fullness of joy — at your right hand are pleasures forevermore — this is the God you serve — not a God of austerity and spiritual duty. A God of fullness and joy and pleasure that has no end. Whatever you have been looking for in the temporary things, in the achievements and the pleasures that fade, he has the real version. The fullness that you were made for is found in him — draw close — you will find what you were actually looking for." },
    { v:"Surely your goodness and unfailing love will pursue me all the days of my life.", r:"Psalm 23:6", d:"Surely goodness and mercy shall follow me all the days of my life — follow — pursue — chase. Like something that is after you. Goodness and mercy are not things you have to catch up to. They are behind you, following you through every day of your life — you cannot outrun God's goodness. You cannot move too far ahead of his mercy — they are always on your trail. Let that be the thing that walks with you through today." },
    { v:"I remain confident of this: I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living.", r:"Psalm 27:13", d:"I remain confident of this: I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living — not in heaven eventually — here — now — in this life. The Psalmist is not deferring the goodness of God to a future he cannot see. He is believing it for the world he is currently inhabiting. There is goodness God has for you in this life, not just in the next one. Keep your eyes open for it — it is coming. He has not run out of good things to do in you and through you." },
    { v:"Oh, how great is your goodness, which you have stored up for those who fear you.", r:"Psalm 31:19", d:"The goodness God has stored up for those who fear him is abundant beyond what you can measure. It has already been accumulated, already set aside, already prepared. It is waiting for the moment to be released into your life. Whatever you are asking God for, whatever you are trusting him toward, the goodness he has in store for you exceeds your request. His reserves do not run short. What he has prepared for those who walk with him is more than you have thought to ask for." },
    { v:"The Lord is good, a strong refuge when trouble comes. He is close to those who trust in him.", r:"Nahum 1:7", d:"The Lord is good — a strong refuge when trouble comes — he is close to those who trust in him. When trouble arrives, God does not step back to observe from a safe distance — he is close — not arriving, not preparing to help — close. Right now, in the trouble you are already in, he is near. The refuge he offers is not somewhere you have to travel to. It is wherever you are when you turn to him — he is close — trust him." },
    { v:"Oh give thanks to the Lord, for he is good; for his steadfast love endures forever.", r:"Psalm 118:1", d:"His steadfast love endures forever — that word endures is doing tremendous work — it means it does not run out — it does not wear down — it does not expire. The love of God toward you has been exactly what it is today through everything you have ever done and not done — it will be exactly the same tomorrow — you cannot exhaust it — you cannot empty it — you cannot outlast it — the steadfast love of the Lord endures forever. Live like that is actually true." },
    { v:"Blessed is the man who trusts in the Lord, whose trust is the Lord.", r:"Jeremiah 17:7", d:"Blessed is the one who trusts in the Lord, whose confidence is in him — not in their own ability to figure things out. Not in their track record of good decisions — not in favorable circumstances — in the Lord. That kind of trust produces a particular kind of person, someone who is not shaken when everything shifts, who is not undone by uncertainty, whose roots hold when drought comes. Build your confidence in the right place — it is the only foundation that never moves." },
    { v:"A joyful heart is good medicine, but a crushed spirit dries up the bones.", r:"Proverbs 17:22", d:"A joyful heart is good medicine. The condition of your inner life has direct physical consequences. What you carry emotionally and spiritually shows up in your body — joy heals — bitterness destroys — peace restores — anxiety depletes — this is not just metaphor — it is physiology. Taking care of your soul is taking care of your health. Pursue joy not just as a spiritual discipline but as a physical necessity — it is medicine — take it." },
    { v:"Search for the Lord and for his strength; continually seek him.", r:"Psalm 105:4", d:"Seek the Lord and his strength — seek his presence continually. Not occasionally, not when you feel spiritually motivated — continually. As the default orientation of your life. The seeking of God is not an add-on to a life built around other things — it is the thread that runs through everything. When seeking him is the constant of your life, his strength and his presence are available in every moment, not just the ones you have designated as spiritual." },
    { v:"Remember the wonders he has performed, his miracles, and the rulings he has given.", r:"Psalm 105:5", d:"Remember the wonders he has performed. His miracles and the rulings he has given. Memory is a spiritual discipline. It requires intentional effort to hold onto what God has done when the present difficulty is loud — keep a record. Write down what he has done for you. Return to it when the current season is hard. The God who did those things is the same God you are trusting right now. Let what he has done fuel your faith for what he is going to do." },
    { v:"In all your ways acknowledge him, and he will make straight your paths.", r:"Proverbs 3:6", d:"Acknowledge him in all your ways and he will make your paths straight — all your ways is not selective. It is not just the obviously spiritual decisions — all of them — the small choices and the large ones. The everyday decisions you make without thinking and the ones you agonize over. Bring God into all of it. Let him into every room of your life. The path that is straight is the one he directs. Stop making decisions in rooms you have not let him into." },
    { v:"Psalm 84:11b", r:"No good thing does he withhold from those who walk uprightly.", d:"God's withholding is never negligence — it is wisdom. What has not come yet, what seems delayed or denied, is held in the hands of a Father who can see what you cannot — he is not stingy — he is protective. Trust that what he is keeping from you right now is for your good, and that what he will release in the right season will be worth the wait — walk uprightly — the good things are coming." },
    { v:"Jeremiah 31:3", r:"I have loved you with an everlasting love; therefore I have continued my faithfulness to you.", d:"Everlasting love is the kind that did not start when you got it together and will not stop when you fall apart — it existed before you did — it will outlast everything you will ever do wrong. God did not begin loving you as a response to your choices. He loved you first and the faithfulness that followed is the result of that love — you are not earning or losing this — it was given before you could do either." },
    { v:"Now may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father comfort you and strengthen you.", r:"2 Thessalonians 2:16–17", d:"God himself, the Father who loved you and gave you eternal encouragement and good hope through grace, will strengthen your heart and establish you in every good work and word. The encouragement you receive from him is eternal — not circumstantial — not mood-dependent — grounded in grace. When you feel weak, when the work feels pointless, when you wonder if any of it matters, this is what holds you. God himself is doing the establishing — the work will stand." },
    { v:"My soul will be satisfied as with fat and rich food, and my mouth will praise you with joyful lips.", r:"Psalm 63:5", d:"My soul will be satisfied as with fat and rich food, and my mouth will praise you with joyful lips. David wrote this in a dry, weary land, possibly during exile — not in a season of abundance — in scarcity, he is speaking of being richly satisfied. The soul that finds its satisfaction in God is not dependent on external conditions to feel full. It is fed from a source that does not dry up in drought. Bring your hunger to God — he satisfies differently than anything else." },
  ],
  11: [
    { v:"Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you, and learn from me, for I am gentle and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls.", r:"Matthew 11:28-29", d:"Come to me, all who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke and learn from me, for I am gentle and humble in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. The rest Jesus offers is not the rest of inactivity. It is the rest of working alongside someone whose yoke fits, whose pace is sustainable, whose expectations of you are calibrated to who you actually are. The weariness you feel right now is not a disqualifier — it is the invitation — come." },
    { v:"Take my yoke upon you. Let me teach you, because I am humble and gentle at heart, and you will find rest for your souls.", r:"Matthew 11:29", d:"Learn from me, for I am gentle and humble in heart. Jesus describes himself not as impressive or powerful but as gentle — that is the teacher you are learning from. He will not berate you for moving slowly or failing repeatedly. His gentleness is not weakness. It is the strength of someone who has no need to prove himself and no interest in crushing what is already bruised. Bring your whole self to him — he is safe." },
    { v:"For my yoke is easy to bear, and the burden I give you is light.", r:"Matthew 11:30", d:"My yoke is easy and my burden is light. That does not mean the Christian life has no cost — it means the yoke fits the one wearing it — a well-fitted yoke does not chafe. The burden God gives you is sized for you and carried alongside him. The heaviness you feel may be from something you were never meant to carry. Put down what is not yours. Take up what he is actually asking. The difference in weight will tell you which is which." },
    { v:"The Lord is my shepherd; I have all that I need. He lets me rest in green meadows.", r:"Psalm 23:1–2", d:"The Lord is my shepherd. I have all that I need — he lets me rest — he leads me beside peaceful streams. The one who tends you knows when you need to stop. The shepherd does not drive the sheep until they collapse. He leads them to rest, to still water, to green meadows. The rest is not incidental — it is part of the tending. If you feel like you cannot stop, consider whether you are following the shepherd or running ahead of him." },
    { v:"He leads me beside peaceful streams. He renews my strength.", r:"Psalm 23:2–3", d:"He renews my strength. He guides me along right paths, bringing honor to his name. The guidance that comes from God is not always the path you would have chosen. But it brings honor to his name, which means it is exactly right for the story he is writing through your life. Trust the leading even when the path is unexpected. He is guiding you somewhere that reflects who he is — follow him." },
    { v:"He guides me along right paths, bringing honor to his name.", r:"Psalm 23:3", d:"He guides me along right paths, bringing honor to his name. The path God leads you on is not only for your benefit — it serves a larger purpose — it reflects who he is. Which means every step of faithfulness in the right direction, every choice to follow him when it would be easier not to, is part of a story that is bigger than just your life. You are walking in a way that honors God — that is not a small thing." },
    { v:"Isaiah 55:11", r:"So shall my word be that goes out from my mouth; it shall not return to me empty, but it shall accomplish that which I purpose, and shall succeed in the thing for which I sent it.", d:"God's word does not go out without accomplishing what it was sent to do. Every promise he has spoken over your life is still in motion — what he has said is not idle — it is working. The seasons where nothing seems to be happening are often the seasons where the word of God is doing its deepest work, underground, unseen, preparing for a harvest that is coming — what he said will succeed — it always does." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord forever, for the Lord God is an everlasting rock.", r:"Isaiah 26:4", d:"Trust in the Lord forever, for the Lord God is an everlasting rock — the rock does not move. It does not shift with the weather or crack under pressure or erode over time. When everything around you is unstable, when the ground under your plans has shifted, when the people you were counting on have disappointed you, he is still the same — forever. His reliability is not conditional — build on him. He is the only foundation that has never once failed." },
    { v:"Isaiah 30:18", r:"Therefore the Lord waits to be gracious to you, and therefore he exalts himself to show mercy to you. For the Lord is a God of justice; blessed are all those who wait for him.", d:"God is waiting to be gracious to you — both of you are waiting. He is waiting for the right moment to release what he has prepared — you are waiting for it to arrive. The blessing in this verse belongs to those who wait for him — the waiting is not passive. It is an act of trust that says I believe the right time is coming and I will not force what belongs in God's hands — wait well — the grace is coming." },
    { v:"Then you will have healing for your body and strength for your bones.", r:"Proverbs 3:8", d:"Honor God with your body, with what you eat, with how you rest, with the care you give to the physical life he has given you, and it will be healing to your flesh. Physical health and spiritual faithfulness are not separate tracks — they are connected. The reverence you bring to God, the way you fear him and turn from what harms you, it has a physical consequence. How you treat the life he gave you matters to him — treat it accordingly." },
    { v:"Psalm 62:8", r:"Trust in him at all times, O people; pour out your heart before him; God is a refuge for us.", d:"Pour out your heart before him — not the polished version — not the prayer that sounds spiritual enough — everything. The anger, the confusion, the grief, the things you are embarrassed to admit you feel — pour it out. God already knows it — you are not informing him of something new. You are giving yourself permission to be fully known by the only one who can actually handle everything you are carrying — he is the refuge. Come all the way in." },
    { v:"Be still, and know that I am God.", r:"Psalm 46:10", d:"Be still and know that I am God. The stillness he is asking for is not the absence of trouble. The psalm is set in the middle of nations in uproar and kingdoms falling. Be still in the middle of that. Stop the striving, stop the anxious running, stop trying to fix what you were never equipped to fix — he is God — you are not. Let that truth do its work — what he says he will do, he will do — you do not have to manage it. Be still and let him be God." },
    { v:"I lay down and slept, yet I woke up in safety, for the Lord was watching over me.", r:"Psalm 3:5", d:"I lay down and slept — i woke again — the Lord was watching over me. David wrote this while his own son was trying to kill him and half the country had turned against him — and he slept. Not because the danger was not real but because the keeping of the night belonged to someone he trusted completely. The fact that you woke up this morning is an act of God's faithfulness — he watched over you through the night — he will watch over you through today." },
    { v:"In peace I will lie down and sleep, for you alone, O Lord, will keep me safe.", r:"Psalm 4:8", d:"In peace I will lie down and sleep, for you alone, O Lord, make me dwell in safety. The peace David describes here is not the peace that comes after the threat is resolved. It is peace in the presence of the threat, because of who is standing watch — he does not say things are safe. He says God makes him dwell in safety — that is a different kind of security. Not circumstantial but rooted in the one who does not sleep and does not fail." },
    { v:"He will not let you stumble; the one who watches over you will not slumber.", r:"Psalm 121:3", d:"He will not let your foot slip — the one who watches over you does not slumber. There is no moment when you are unprotected — no gap in the coverage — no shift change where someone less attentive takes over. The Lord who keeps you is always awake, always watching, always positioned to catch what would cause you to fall. You are not walking this path without a keeper — step with confidence." },
    { v:"The Lord himself watches over you! The Lord stands beside you as your protective shade.", r:"Psalm 121:5", d:"The Lord himself watches over you — the Lord is your protective shade. He stands at your right hand, the side of greatest vulnerability, the side most exposed in battle. Whatever you are walking into today that feels dangerous or uncertain, God is positioned at the place where you are most exposed — not behind you at a safe distance. Beside you, at your most vulnerable point — you are not unguarded — you are covered." },
    { v:"The Lord keeps you from all harm and watches over your life.", r:"Psalm 121:7", d:"The Lord keeps you from all harm — he watches over your life — all harm — not most harm. Not the threats he deems significant enough to address — all. What he is guarding is not just your safety in the immediate moment. He is watching over your life, the whole arc of it, the beginning and end and everything in between — you are under comprehensive coverage. Nothing gets through to you without going through him first." },
    { v:"The Lord keeps watch over you as you come and go, both now and forever.", r:"Psalm 121:8", d:"The Lord keeps watch over you as you come and go, both now and forever. Every departure and every arrival. Every ordinary movement of an ordinary day. Every transition and every threshold. God is watching over all of it, now and forever — he is not selectively attentive to the big moments. He is present in the coming and going, the mundane movement of a life, all of it held in his keeping — you are never outside of his watch." },
    { v:"God gives rest to his loved ones.", r:"Psalm 127:2", d:"God gives rest to his loved ones — not as the reward for enough productivity — not after you have earned the break. As a gift, to those he loves. The grinding, the excessive striving, the sacrificing of sleep for the appearance of progress, God calls it vain — he is not impressed by your exhaustion — he wants you rested — rest is not weakness. Rest is the act of trusting that God works while you are asleep and nothing is lost when you stop." },
    { v:"Psalm 46:5", r:"God is within her, she will not fall; God will help her at break of day.", d:"God is within her. Not standing guard outside while she manages things alone on the inside — within. His presence is interior, embedded, part of her — she will not fall because of who she carries. Not because she is strong enough not to — because the one inside her is. At break of day, when the night has been long and the morning brings its own set of demands, his help is there — he meets you at the start of every day." },
    { v:"Therefore do not be anxious, saying, What shall we eat? or What shall we drink? or What shall we wear? For the Gentiles seek after all these things, and your heavenly Father knows that you need them all.", r:"Matthew 6:31-32", d:"Your Father already knows what you need before you ask. You are not approaching a God who is unaware of your situation and hoping to bring it to his attention — he already knows. The anxiety about food and clothing and basic provision, the worry about whether there will be enough, is rooted in the assumption that no one is paying attention. God is paying attention — he knows. Trust the one who sees your need completely." },
    { v:"Numbers 6:24-26", r:"The Lord bless you and keep you; the Lord make his face shine on you and be gracious to you; the Lord turn his face toward you and give you peace.", d:"God spoke these words over Israel as a blessing given through the priests. His face turned toward you. In the ancient world, the face of the king turned toward you was the sign of favor — turned away was rejection. God turns his face toward you in blessing, in grace, in peace — he is not looking away — he is not watching with disapproval. He is turned toward you with everything that blessing means." },
    { v:"The Lord is near to all who call on him, to all who call on him in truth.", r:"Psalm 145:18", d:"The Lord is near to all who call on him. Near to all who call on him in truth — the nearness is universal and it is real. Anyone who calls on God with a genuine heart finds him near — not eventually — not after they have sorted themselves out — the nearness comes with the calling — you do not have to travel to find him — you do not have to earn access. Call on him with an honest heart and discover that he was already close." },
    { v:"The Lord is a stronghold for the oppressed, a stronghold in times of trouble.", r:"Psalm 9:9", d:"The Lord is a stronghold for the oppressed, a stronghold in times of trouble. He is not a God who shows up only for the strong. He is specifically and deliberately the stronghold for those who are being pressed down, overlooked, disadvantaged, struggling under a weight they did not choose. If you are in that place right now, you are the specific person this verse was written for — he is your stronghold — run to him." },
    { v:"When doubts filled my mind, your comfort gave me renewed hope and cheer.", r:"Psalm 94:19", d:"When doubts fill your mind, God's comfort gives renewed hope and cheer. Not when you have sorted out all the doubts first — when they fill your mind. In the middle of the uncertainty and the confusion and the questions that do not have clean answers. His comfort enters the doubt. It does not demand that the doubt be resolved before comfort is available. Come to him with the full weight of your uncertainty. His comfort meets you exactly there." },
    { v:"The Lord is close to the brokenhearted; he rescues those whose spirits are crushed.", r:"Psalm 34:18", d:"The Lord is close to the brokenhearted — he rescues those whose spirits are crushed. The crushing is real — he does not minimize it — but he is close in it — not arriving to help eventually. Already close to you in the broken place. If your heart is broken right now, if your spirit feels like it has been crushed, the closeness of God is not something you have to achieve — it is already the reality — he is already there — let him be near." },
    { v:"Deuteronomy 33:27", r:"The eternal God is your dwelling place, and underneath are the everlasting arms.", d:"Underneath are the everlasting arms — not beside you — not above you at a safe distance — underneath. Holding you up from below. The arms that sustain you are everlasting, which means they do not tire, they do not weaken, they do not release. Whatever you are afraid of falling from, whatever feels like it might give way beneath you, there is something holding you up that does not have a breaking point — he is underneath — you will not fall further than his arms." },
    { v:"Morning, noon, and night I cry out in my distress, and the Lord hears my voice.", r:"Psalm 55:17", d:"Morning, noon, and night I cry out in my distress — and the Lord hears my voice. Three times a day, David brought the same hard thing to God because the hard thing had not resolved. God did not get tired of hearing it. He did not grow impatient with the repetition — he heard — every time. If you have been bringing the same prayer to God repeatedly and wondering if he has heard, the answer is yes — he hears your voice — keep bringing it." },
    { v:"Psalm 91:2", r:"I will say to the Lord, My refuge and my fortress, my God, in whom I trust.", d:"This is not just a description of God. It is a declaration the speaker makes over their own life — i will say to the Lord. Actively, out loud, with intention: You are my refuge — you are my fortress — you are my God and I trust you. Speaking truth about who God is to you changes something. It aligns your heart with what is real — say it today — say it out loud. Let your own ears hear you declare where your trust is." },
    { v:"When I am afraid, I put my trust in you.", r:"Psalm 56:3", d:"When I am afraid, I will trust in you — not if I am afraid — when. David assumes the fear will come — he does not pretend it will not. What he decides in advance is what he will do with the fear when it arrives — he will trust. That is the decision made before the moment, so that when fear shows up, the response is already determined. Make that decision now — when fear comes, you will trust. Do not wait for the fear to hit before you decide." },
  ],
  12: [
    { v:"The unfolding of your words gives light; it imparts understanding to the simple.", r:"Psalm 119:130", d:"The unfolding of your words gives light — it gives understanding to the simple — not the scholar — the simple. The person who comes to the Word honestly, without pretense, without the need to impress anyone with their knowledge, receives understanding. The light does not require your complexity — it requires your openness. Open the Word with a willing heart and let the light come in — you do not have to be an expert — you just have to be willing to receive." },
    { v:"Whom have I in heaven but you? And there is nothing on earth that I desire besides you.", r:"Psalm 73:25", d:"Whom do I have in heaven but you?. And there is nothing on earth that I desire besides you. Asaph arrived at this after almost losing his faith. He had been comparing himself to the wicked who prospered and nearly concluded that following God was pointless. And at the end of that crisis, this is what remained: nothing compares to God. Not the things that seemed to be working for the people who were not following him — nothing — he is better than all of it." },
    { v:"The path of the righteous is like the light of dawn, which shines brighter and brighter until full day.", r:"Proverbs 4:18", d:"The path of the righteous is like the first gleam of dawn, shining ever brighter until the full light of day — you may be at the dawn — barely light. Barely able to see what is ahead — that is okay. The direction matters more than the current level of light — you are moving toward full day — the brightness will increase as you walk. Do not judge where you are going by how dim it looks right now. You are on a path that gets clearer — keep walking." },
    { v:"You are the light of the world — like a city on a hilltop that cannot be hidden.", r:"Matthew 5:14", d:"You are the light of the world. Not you will be, when you are further along, when you have things more figured out — you are. Right now, with everything you are currently carrying, in the middle of everything that is still being worked out in you — you are light — a city on a hill cannot be hidden — you do not have to make yourself visible. You just have to be who you are in Christ. The light will do what light does — it shines." },
    { v:"I am the light of the world. If you follow me, you won't have to walk in darkness.", r:"John 8:12", d:"I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will never walk in darkness but will have the light of life. Following Jesus is not just a moral decision — it is a navigational one — it changes what you can see — the things that looked like dead ends look different. The path that seemed closed opens — what was confusing becomes clearer. Following him does not remove all difficulty but it removes the darkness from it — you have access to a light that changes everything." },
    { v:"For everything there is a season, a time for every activity under heaven.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:1", d:"There is a time for everything — a season for every activity under heaven. The season you are in right now was not a mistake and it will not last forever. God has appointed times for every part of your life: times to work and times to rest, times to grieve and times to celebrate, times to hold on and times to let go. The wisdom is in recognizing which season you are in and responding accordingly — stop fighting the season — find God in it." },
    { v:"Yet God has made everything beautiful for its own time.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:11", d:"God has made everything beautiful in its time — not everything is beautiful right now — not every season looks like what you hoped. But he has built a beauty into the timing of things that you may not be able to see from inside the middle of it. The pain of this season does not mean it is wrong or that God is absent. It means you are in a time that has not yet finished producing what it was sent to produce. Trust the timing of the one who makes everything beautiful." },
    { v:"I know that there is nothing better for people than to be happy and to do good while they live.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:12", d:"There is nothing better than to be happy and to do good while we live. After all the searching, all the testing of wisdom and pleasure and work and accomplishment, Qoheleth lands here — be happy — do good — that is it — not the biggest platform or the most impressive legacy. Joy and goodness in the ordinary life in front of you. Do not spend your life reaching for what Ecclesiastes says will not satisfy — be present — do good. That is what the wisest man concluded after examining everything." },
    { v:"Here now is my final conclusion: Fear God and obey his commands, for this is everyone's duty.", r:"Ecclesiastes 12:13", d:"Fear God and keep his commandments, for this is the duty of everyone. After examining pleasure, work, wisdom, achievement, and finding all of them hollow without God, this is the conclusion. Everything reduces to this: honor him and obey him — not a long list of requirements. The whole duty of a human life in one sentence — what are you building your life around? — measure it against this. If it is not bringing you back to fear him and follow him, it will not satisfy." },
    { v:"Where shall I go from your Spirit? Or where shall I flee from your presence? If I ascend to heaven, you are there; if I make my bed in Sheol, you are there.", r:"Psalm 139:7-8", d:"Where can I flee from your presence?. If I go to heaven, you are there. If I go to the depths, you are there — there is nowhere God is not. That means there is nowhere you can go where you have lost him, nowhere so dark or so far that his presence does not reach. This is not meant to feel like surveillance — it is meant to feel like freedom — you cannot fall outside of his reach. You cannot wander beyond where he can find you — he is everywhere — you are never truly alone." },
    { v:"Even before a word is on my tongue, behold, O Lord, you know it altogether.", r:"Psalm 139:4", d:"Before a word is on your tongue, God knows it completely — he knows every thought before it forms into language. He knows the prayer before you find the words for it. He knows the confession before you gather the courage to make it — you are completely known. Nothing you bring to him will surprise him. Nothing you reveal will change what he already sees. Come to him fully — he already knows it all — the only thing left to do is say it." },
    { v:"How precious to me are your thoughts, O God! How vast is the sum of them! If I would count them, they are more than the sand. I awake, and I am still with you.", r:"Psalm 139:17-18", d:"How precious to me are your thoughts, O God. How vast is the sum of them. If I would count them, they are more than the sand — i awake, and I am still with you. God's thoughts toward you are innumerable and they are precious, costly, weighted with his love for you. When you wake up in the morning and the day begins, you are still with him — the night did not interrupt it. Whatever you woke up worrying about, you woke up still in his thoughts — start from there." },
    { v:"I can never escape from your Spirit! I can never get away from your presence!", r:"Psalm 139:7", d:"Where can I go from your Spirit?. — where can I flee from your presence?. — the answer is nowhere. The omnipresence of God is not a weight — it is a comfort. There is no place so dark, no failure so severe, no season so dry that you have moved outside of his presence. He is with you in the places you are most ashamed of. He is with you in the places you are most afraid — you have never once been where he was not." },
    { v:"You go before me and follow me. You place your hand of blessing on my head.", r:"Psalm 139:5", d:"You hem me in, behind and before, and you lay your hand upon me — behind and before — the past and the future. God is present in both directions. The things you have already been through that are still shaping you, he was there. The things ahead that you cannot see and cannot prepare for, he is already there. And his hand is on you right now, in the present. Completely surrounded by his presence — you are held from every direction." },
    { v:"Such knowledge is too wonderful for me, too great for me to understand!", r:"Psalm 139:6", d:"Such knowledge is too wonderful for me, too lofty for me to attain. There is a kind of wonder that is the right response to something too large for your mind to hold. You do not have to understand the full depth of how intimately God knows you — you just have to receive it. Let the wonder do its work. Something about you is so worth knowing that the God of everything is attending to every detail — that is enough to stop you in your tracks." },
    { v:"For his unfailing love toward those who fear him is as great as the height of the heavens above the earth.", r:"Psalm 103:11", d:"As high as the heavens are above the earth, so great is his love for those who fear him. The distance described here is the maximum the ancient world could conceive — they were not speaking of light years. They were gesturing at something so vast it cannot be measured. That is the scale of God's love for you — not a little love — not proportional to your faithfulness. As high as the heavens — immeasurable — that is what is toward you right now." },
    { v:"He has removed our sins as far from us as the east is from the west.", r:"Psalm 103:12", d:"As far as the east is from the west, so far has he removed our transgressions from us. East and west do not converge — they have no meeting point — the distance is infinite — that is where God has sent your sin. Not suppressed it, not filed it for review, not stored it where it might be brought back up — removed it — infinitely far from you. The thing you are still carrying shame about, the failure you keep returning to, he has sent it to a place that does not exist on any map." },
    { v:"The Lord is like a father to his children, tender and compassionate to those who fear him.", r:"Psalm 103:13", d:"As a father has compassion on his children, so the Lord has compassion on those who fear him. The compassion of a good father is not generated by the child's performance — it comes from the relationship itself. From knowing who the child is, where they came from, what they are made of. God's compassion toward you is that same quality of knowing tenderness — he knows what you are made of — he remembers you are dust — and from that knowing, he is compassionate." },
    { v:"For he knows how weak we are; he remembers we are only dust.", r:"Psalm 103:14", d:"He knows how weak we are — he remembers we are only dust. God does not hold you to a standard that ignores your limitations — he made you — he knows the material. When you fail, when you fall short, when you do not have enough of what the situation requires, he is not surprised — he remembered before you forgot. The expectations he holds for you are calibrated to who you actually are, not to who you imagine you should be — he knows your frame." },
    { v:"But the love of the Lord remains forever with those who fear him.", r:"Psalm 103:17", d:"The love of the Lord remains forever with those who fear him — not until they fail. Not until they have a season of distance — forever. The steadfastness described here is not earned and it cannot be lost. It extends to the children of those who fear God, generation after generation. What God started in your life has implications beyond you. Your faithfulness is planting something that will outlast your lifetime — the love that holds you is multigenerational and permanent." },
    { v:"Psalm 91:11", r:"For he will command his angels concerning you to guard you in all your ways.", d:"Angels are commanded concerning you — not available in case you ask — commanded — dispatched. Working on your behalf — in all your ways — the protection is comprehensive and it is active. You are not going through your life with a distant God who hopes things work out for you. You are going through it with heaven actively engaged on your behalf. Walk with that awareness today." },
    { v:"May the God of peace himself sanctify you completely, and may your whole spirit and soul and body be kept blameless at the coming of our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"1 Thessalonians 5:23", d:"May the God of peace sanctify you through and through — your whole spirit, soul, and body kept blameless. God is not only concerned with your spiritual life — he wants your whole person — every part of you. The body you are taking care of in here, the mind you are feeding and guarding, the soul you are attending to in prayer, all of it matters to him — he is not dividing you into spiritual and secular. He is working on the whole person he made you to be." },
    { v:"Psalm 91:4", r:"He will cover you with his feathers, and under his wings you will find refuge; his faithfulness will be your shield and rampart.", d:"Under his wings you will find refuge — the image is not majestic — it is intimate — a bird covering her young with her own body. God offers that kind of protection. Close, warm, personal, using himself as the covering. His faithfulness is your shield. Not your own performance or your own strength or your own careful management of circumstances — his faithfulness. That is a shield that does not depend on you to hold it up." },
    { v:"For a child is born to us, a son is given to us. And he will be called: Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.", r:"Isaiah 9:6", d:"His name shall be called Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace. Every name is a claim about who he is and what he offers — wonder beyond your understanding. Power beyond your limitation — a Father who will not leave — a peace that outlasts every storm. He was born in a manger but every name given to him speaks of a scope that creation itself cannot contain. The one who came as a child holds everything together." },
    { v:"And the Word became flesh and dwelt among us, and we have seen his glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth.", r:"John 1:14", d:"The Word became flesh and dwelt among us. God did not manage the human problem from a distance — he entered it — he took on a body. He lived in a specific place at a specific time, ate food, felt cold, knew exhaustion, wept at a grave. The incarnation means there is no human experience that is outside of what God has touched. He is not unfamiliar with what you are going through — he has been here." },
    { v:"Jesus said to him, I am the way, and the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.", r:"John 14:6", d:"I am the way, the truth, and the life — not one way among many — the way. When the path forward is unclear, when you cannot find the truth in a world full of noise, when you are looking for a life that is actually worth living, the answer is the same in every case — he is the answer. Not a philosophy, not a method, not a set of principles — a person. The way, the truth, the life is a person you can actually know." },
    { v:"The night is almost gone; the day of salvation will soon be here. So remove your dark deeds like dirty clothes, and put on the shining armor of right living.", r:"Romans 13:12", d:"The night is nearly over — the day is almost here. Take off the works of darkness and put on the armor of light. Every day you wake up is a day closer to the fullness of what God is bringing — the darkness of this age is not permanent. You are living in the last act of a very long story. How you live right now, the choices you make, the character you build, the faithfulness you carry, it all matters because the day is coming — live toward it." },
    { v:"My soul waits for the Lord more than watchmen for the morning, more than watchmen for the morning.", r:"Psalm 130:6", d:"My soul waits for the Lord more than watchmen wait for the morning. The watchmen knew the morning was coming — that was certain. The only question was when — they waited with expectation, not despair — that is the posture of hope — not wondering if God will come through — knowing he will — watching for it. Living in the certain expectation that what he promised is on its way. Let your soul wait like that — not hopeless — watchful." },
    { v:"For our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God.", r:"2 Corinthians 5:21", d:"God made Christ, who knew no sin, to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God — the exchange is complete and it is staggering. Everything that was yours, every failure, every shortcoming, every sin, was transferred to him. Everything that is his, the full righteousness of God himself, was transferred to you — not someday — not partially — already. You are the righteousness of God in Christ — walk like it." },
    { v:"Psalm 91:1", r:"Whoever dwells in the shelter of the Most High will rest in the shadow of the Almighty.", d:"Dwelling in the shelter of the Most High is not a one-time decision. It is a consistent, daily, intentional choice to stay close — to keep your life positioned under his covering. The shadow belongs to whoever dwells, not just to whoever visited once. The rest available to you in him is proportional to the closeness you choose to maintain. Draw near and stay near — the shelter is real — make it your home." },
    { v:"Being confident of this, I know that I will remain and continue with you all, for your progress and joy in the faith.", r:"Philippians 1:25", d:"Paul chose to stay not for his own benefit but for the sake of the people God had placed in his care. His joy and progress in the faith mattered more to Paul than his own preference to go. There is a version of faithfulness that looks like staying when leaving would be easier. Staying in the hard relationship. Staying in the calling that is costing you. Staying in the race when your legs are tired. Someone needs your remaining — do not leave too early." },
  ],
};

function getTodayScripture() {
  const now = new Date();
  const month = now.getMonth() + 1;
  const day = now.getDate();
  const mm = String(month).padStart(2,"0");
  const dd = String(day).padStart(2,"0");

  // Special dates first
  if (SPECIAL[`${mm}-${dd}`]) return { ...SPECIAL[`${mm}-${dd}`], isSpecial: true };

  // Liturgical season overrides
  const season = getLiturgicalSeason(now);
  if (SEASONS[season]) return { ...SEASONS[season], isSpecial: true };

  // Pick from monthly array by day
  const arr = BY_MONTH[month] || BY_MONTH[1];
  const entry = arr[(day - 1) % arr.length];
  return { v: entry.v, r: entry.r, d: entry.d || null, season: null, isSunday: now.getDay() === 0 };
}

// ── Sunday reflection prompts ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
const SUNDAY_PROMPTS = [
  "What is one thing your body did this week that you are grateful for?",
  "Where did you feel God's strength most clearly in your training this week?",
  "What would it look like to honor God with your body more fully this coming week?",
  "What is one area of your health you want to bring to God in prayer today?",
  "Where did you hold back this week — in training, in rest, or in trusting God?",
  "What did this week's effort reveal about your character? What do you want to build on?",
  "How can the strength you are building serve the people around you this week?",
  "What do you need to release — a comparison, a shame, a fear — before the new week begins?",
];

function getSundayPrompt() {
  const week = Math.floor(new Date().getDate() / 7);
  return SUNDAY_PROMPTS[week % SUNDAY_PROMPTS.length];
}

// ── Cross SVG ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function CrossMark({ color = "#555" }) {
  // Vertical bar: full height (18px)
  // Horizontal bar: narrower (10px wide), positioned 1/3 from top
  return (
    <svg width="12" height="18" viewBox="0 0 12 18" fill="none" style={{ flexShrink: 0, marginTop: "1px" }}>
      <rect x="5" y="0" width="2" height="18" rx="1" fill={color} />
      <rect x="1" y="5" width="10" height="2" rx="1" fill={color} />
    </svg>
  );
}

// ── Component ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export default function DailyScripture({ accent = "#2563a8", inHeader = false }) {
  const today = new Date().toISOString().slice(0, 10);
  const notesKey = `scripture_notes_${today}`;
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(false);
  const [notes, setNotes] = useState(() => {
    try { return localStorage.getItem(notesKey) || ""; } catch { return ""; }
  });

  const scripture = getTodayScripture();
  const isSunday = new Date().getDay() === 0;
  const sundayPrompt = isSunday ? getSundayPrompt() : null;

  function handleNotes(e) {
    setNotes(e.target.value);
    try { localStorage.setItem(notesKey, e.target.value); } catch {}
  }

  if (!scripture) return null;

  const seasonLabel = scripture.season || (isSunday ? "Sunday · Rest & Reflection" : "Today's Word");

  return (
    <div style={{
      ...(inHeader
        ? { margin: "0 0 12px 0", borderRadius: "6px", overflow: "hidden", border: "1px solid #2a2a2a", background: "#1a1a1a" }
        : { margin: "10px 14px", borderRadius: "10px", overflow: "hidden", border: "1px solid #222", background: "#111" }
      ),
      ...F,
    }}>

      {/* Always-visible header — tap to expand */}
      <button onClick={() => setExpanded(p => !p)} style={{
        width: "100%", background: "none", border: "none", cursor: "pointer",
        padding: inHeader ? "10px 12px" : "13px 15px",
        display: "flex", alignItems: "flex-start", gap: "10px", textAlign: "left", ...F,
      }}>
        <CrossMark color={accent} />
        <div style={{ flex: 1, minWidth: 0 }}>
          <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.22em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: accent, marginBottom: "5px" }}>
            {seasonLabel}
          </div>
          {/* Full verse always shown */}
          <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#e8e0cc", lineHeight: "1.7", fontStyle: "italic" }}>
            "{scripture.v}"
          </div>
          {/* Reference always shown */}
          <div style={{ fontSize: "10px", color: accent, marginTop: "6px", letterSpacing: "0.06em" }}>
            — {scripture.r}
          </div>
        </div>
        <span style={{ color: "#444", fontSize: "10px", flexShrink: 0, paddingTop: "2px" }}>
          {expanded ? "▲" : "▼"}
        </span>
      </button>

      {/* Expanded section — reflection + notes */}
      {expanded && (
        <div style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>

          {/* Reflection */}
          {scripture.d && (
            <div style={{ padding: "14px 15px 12px" }}>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#555", marginBottom: "9px" }}>
                Reflection
              </div>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#b8b0a0", lineHeight: "1.85" }}>
                {scripture.d}
              </div>
            </div>
          )}

          {/* Sunday prompt */}
          {isSunday && sundayPrompt && (
            <div style={{ padding: "10px 15px 12px", borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#555", marginBottom: "9px" }}>
                This week
              </div>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#b8b0a0", lineHeight: "1.8", fontStyle: "italic" }}>
                {sundayPrompt}
              </div>
            </div>
          )}

          {/* Personal notes */}
          <div style={{ padding: "10px 15px 14px", borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#444", marginBottom: "7px" }}>
              Your notes
            </div>
            <textarea
              value={notes}
              onChange={handleNotes}
              placeholder="Add your own reflection..."
              style={{
                width: "100%", boxSizing: "border-box",
                background: "#1a1a1a", border: "1px solid #2a2a2a",
                borderRadius: "5px", color: "#c8c0b0", fontSize: "12px",
                lineHeight: "1.65", padding: "8px 10px", resize: "none",
                outline: "none", minHeight: "70px", ...F,
              }}
              rows={3}
            />
          </div>

        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
